# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bank-of-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A referendum on Scottish independence from the United Kingdom was held in Scotland on 18 September 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The referendum question was "Should Scotland be an independent country?", which voters answered with "Yes" or "No".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The turnout of 84.6% was the highest recorded for an election or referendum in the United Kingdom since the January 1910 general election, which was held before the introduction of universal suffrage.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 set out the arrangements for the referendum and was passed by the Scottish Parliament in November 2013, following an agreement between the devolved Scottish government and the Government of the United Kingdom.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The independence proposal required a simple majority to pass.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] All European Union (EU) or Commonwealth citizens residing in Scotland age 16 or over could vote, with some exceptions, which produced a total electorate of almost 4,300,000 people.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This was the first time that the electoral franchise was extended to include 16- and 17-year-olds in Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Yes Scotland was the main campaign group for independence, while Better Together was the main campaign group in favour of maintaining the union.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Many other campaign groups, political parties, businesses, newspapers, and prominent individuals were also involved.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Prominent issues raised during the referendum included what currency an independent Scotland would use, public expenditure, EU membership, and North Sea oil.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] An exit poll revealed that retention of the pound sterling was the deciding factor for those who voted No, while "disaffection with Westminster politics" was the deciding factor for those who voted Yes.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Kingdom of Scotland and the Kingdom of England were established as independent countries during the Middle Ages.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] After fighting a series of wars during the 14th century, the two monarchies entered a personal union in 1603 (the Union of the Crowns) when James VI of Scotland also became James I of England.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The two nations were temporarily united under one government when Oliver Cromwell was declared Lord Protector of a Commonwealth in 1653, but this was dissolved when the monarchy was restored in 1660.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Scotland and England united to form the Kingdom of Great Britain in 1707 (Wales had already been unilaterally incorporated into England in the mid-16th century).
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scots favoured union to solve the economic problems caused by the failure of the Darien scheme and the English favoured it to secure the Hanoverian line of succession.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Great Britain in turn united with the Kingdom of Ireland in 1801, forming the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Most of Ireland left the Union in 1922 to form the Irish Free State; consequently, the full name of the United Kingdom since 1927 is the *United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland*.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Labour Party was committed to home rule for Scotland in the 1920s, but it slipped down its agenda in the following years.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish National Party (SNP) was founded in 1934, but did not achieve significant electoral success until the 1960s.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A petition calling for home rule, the Scottish Covenant, was signed by 2,000,000 people (out of a population of 5,000,000) in the late 1940s.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As James Callaghan's Labour Government of the late 1970s was pressured by the SNP, Scottish devolution was, for the first time, seriously proposed.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In a 1979 referendum for a devolved Scottish Assembly, a narrow majority of votes were cast in favour of devolution, but this had no effect due to a requirement that the number voting 'Yes' had to exceed 40% of the total electorate.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] No further constitutional reform was proposed until Labour returned to power in a landslide electoral victory in May 1997.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A second Scottish devolution referendum was held later that year, as promised in the Labour election manifesto.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Clear majorities expressed support for both a devolved Scottish Parliament (74.3% in favour) and that Parliament having the power to vary the basic rate of UK income tax (63.5% in favour).
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scotland Act 1998 established the new Scottish Parliament, first elected on 6 May 1999, with power to legislate on unreserved matters within Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A commitment to hold an independence referendum in 2010 was part of the SNP's election manifesto when it contested the 2007 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The press were largely hostile towards the SNP, with a headline for *The Scottish Sun* in May 2007 stating – beside an image of a hangman's noose – "Vote SNP today and you put Scotland's head in the noose".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As a result of that election, the SNP became the largest party in the Scottish Parliament and formed a minority government led by the First Minister, Alex Salmond.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The SNP administration launched a 'National Conversation' as a consultation exercise in August 2007, part of which included a draft referendum bill, the *Referendum (Scotland) Bill*.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] After this, a white paper for the proposed Referendum Bill was published, on 30 November 2009.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It detailed four possible scenarios, with the text of the Bill and Referendum to be revealed later.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The scenarios were: no change; devolution per the Calman Review; further devolution; and full independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government published a draft version of the bill on 25 February 2010 for public consultation; *Scotland's Future: Draft Referendum (Scotland) Bill Consultation Paper* contained a consultation document and a draft version of the bill.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The consultation paper set out the proposed ballot papers, the mechanics of the proposed referendum, and how the proposed referendum was to be regulated.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The third proposal was for full independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the 3rd Scottish Parliament only 50 of 129 MSPs (47 SNP, 2 Greens, and Margo MacDonald) supported a referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government withdrew the bill in September 2010 after failing to secure opposition support.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The SNP repeated its commitment to hold an independence referendum when it published its manifesto for the 2011 Scottish Parliament election.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Days before the election, Salmond said that legislation for a referendum would be proposed in the "second half of the parliament", as he wanted to secure more powers for the Scottish Parliament via the Scotland Bill first.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the election, the SNP won 69 of the 129 seats, securing a majority in a proportional representative voting system.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] UK Prime Minister David Cameron congratulated Salmond on his 'emphatic win', but pledged to campaign for the Union if the SNP carried out their pledge to hold a referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In January 2012, the UK government offered to legislate to provide the Scottish Parliament with the powers to hold a referendum, providing it was 'fair, legal and decisive'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This would set 'terms of reference for the referendum', such as its question(s), elector eligibility, and which body would organise the vote.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As the UK government worked on legal details, including the timing of the vote, Salmond announced an intention to hold the referendum in the autumn of 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Negotiations continued between the two governments until October 2012, when the Edinburgh Agreement was reached.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Independence Referendum (Franchise) Act 2013 was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 27 June 2013 and received Royal Assent on 7 August 2013.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 26 November 2013, the Scottish government published *Scotland's Future*, a 670-page white paper laying out the case for independence and the means by which Scotland might become an independent country.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish Government announced on 21 March 2013 that the referendum would be held on Thursday 18 September 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Some media reports mentioned that 2014 would be the 700th anniversary of the Battle of Bannockburn and that Scotland would also host the 2014 Commonwealth Games and the 2014 Ryder Cup.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Salmond agreed that the presence of these events made 2014 a "good year to hold a referendum".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Convicted prisoners were not able to vote in the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The European Court of Human Rights (ECHR) had ruled that this restriction was unlawful, but Scottish judge Lord Glennie said that he believed the ECHR judgment would apply only to parliamentary elections.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Appeals against his ruling were rejected by the Court of Session in Edinburgh and the UK Supreme Court.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The normal voting age was reduced from 18 to 16 for the referendum, as it was a Scottish National Party policy to reduce the voting age for all elections in Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The move was supported by Labour, the Liberal Democrats and the Scottish Greens.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In January 2012, Labour MSP Elaine Murray led a debate arguing that the franchise should be extended to Scots living outside Scotland, including the approximately 800,000 living in the other parts of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the House of Lords, Baroness Symons argued that the rest of the UK should be allowed to vote on Scottish independence because it would affect the whole country.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This argument was rejected by the UK government, as the Advocate General for Scotland Lord Wallace said that "whether or not Scotland should leave the United Kingdom is a matter for Scotland".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Wallace also pointed to the fact that only two of 11 referendums since 1973 had been across all of the United Kingdom.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Professor John Curtice cited the precedent of the 1973 Northern Ireland sovereignty referendum (the "border poll"), which allowed only those resident in a part of the UK to vote on its sovereignty.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] There was debate as to whether the Scottish Parliament had the power to legislate for a referendum relating to the issue of Scottish independence, as the constitution is a matter reserved to the UK Parliament.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government insisted in 2010 that they could legislate for a referendum, as it would be an "advisory referendum on extending the powers of the Scottish Parliament", whose result would "have no legal effect on the Union".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Lord Wallace, Advocate General for Scotland, said in January 2012 that holding a referendum concerning the constitution would be outside the legislative power of the Scottish Parliament and that private individuals could challenge a Scottish Parliament referendum bill.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The two governments signed the Edinburgh Agreement, which allowed for the temporary transfer of legal authority.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Per the Edinburgh Agreement, the UK government drafted an Order in Council granting the Scottish Parliament the necessary powers to hold, on or before 31 December 2014, an independence referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The draft Order was approved by resolutions of both Houses of Parliament, and the Order ("The Scotland Act 1998 (Modification of Schedule 5) Order 2013"), was approved by Queen Elizabeth II at a meeting of the Privy Council on 12 February 2013.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Under the powers temporarily transferred from Westminster under the section 30 Order, the Scottish Parliament adopted the Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Act was passed by the Scottish Parliament on 14 November 2013 and received Royal Assent on 17 December 2013.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Under section 36 of the Act, it came into force the day after Royal Assent.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission was responsible for overseeing the referendum, "with the exception of the conduct of the poll and announcement of the result, and the giving of grants.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In its role of regulating the campaign and campaign spending, the Electoral Commission will report to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] (...) The poll and count will be managed in the same way as [local] elections, by local returning officers (...) and directed by a Chief Counting Officer".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Edinburgh Agreement stated that the wording of the question would be decided by the Scottish Parliament and reviewed for intelligibility by the Electoral Commission.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Scottish government stated that its preferred question was "Do you agree that Scotland should be an independent country?" The Electoral Commission tested the proposed question along with three other possible versions.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Their research found that the "Do you agree" preface made it a leading question, which would be more likely to garner a positive response.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The question was amended to "Should Scotland be an independent country?", which the Electoral Commission found was the most neutral and concise of the versions tested.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the 2010 Draft Bill, the Scottish government proposed that there would be one designated campaign organisation for each outcome, both of which would be permitted to spend up to £750,000 on their campaign and to send one free mailshot to every household or voter in the referendum franchise.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] There was to be no public funding for campaigns.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Registered political parties were each to be allowed to spend £100,000.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This proposed limit on party spending was increased to £250,000 in 2012.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In 2013, new proposals by the Electoral Commission for the 16-week regulated period preceding the poll were accepted.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] They allowed the two designated campaign organisations to spend up to £1.5 million each and for the parties in Scotland to spend the following amounts: £1,344,000 (SNP); £834,000 (Labour); £396,000 (Conservatives); £201,000 (Liberal Democrats); £150,000 (Greens).
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] An unlimited number of other organisations could register with the Electoral Commission, but their spending was limited to £150,000.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Groups spending more than £250,000 were required to submit audited returns to the Commission by 18 March 2015.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] According to the Scottish government's consultation paper published on 25 February 2010, the cost of the referendum was "likely to be around £9.5 million", mostly spent on running the poll and the count.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Costs would also include the posting of one neutral information leaflet about the referendum to every Scottish household, and one free mailshot to every household or voter in the poll for the designated campaign organisations.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In April 2013, the projected cost of the referendum was £13.3 million; the final administrative cost was £15.85 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign in favour of Scottish independence, Yes Scotland, was launched on 25 May 2012.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Its chief executive was Blair Jenkins, formerly the Director of Broadcasting at STV and Head of News and Current Affairs at both STV and BBC Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign was supported by the SNP, the Scottish Green Party (which also created "its own pro-independence campaign to run alongside Yes Scotland") and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] At its launch, Salmond stated that he hoped one million people in Scotland would sign a declaration of support for independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 22 August 2014, Yes Scotland announced that the one million target had been surpassed.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The campaign in favour of Scotland remaining in the UK, Better Together, was launched on 25 June 2012.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It was led by Alistair Darling, former Chancellor of the Exchequer, and had support from the Conservative Party, Labour Party and Liberal Democrats.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Political advertising on television and radio in the UK was prohibited by the Communications Act 2003, with the exception of permitted party political broadcasts.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Three major cinema chains stopped showing adverts by referendum campaign groups after receiving negative feedback from their customers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In December 2013, the Better Together campaign declared that it had received donations of £2,800,000.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Six-figure contributions were made by businessmen Ian Taylor and Donald Houston, and by author C.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Almost 27,000 donations of under £7,500 had been received by the same date.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Rowling, who announced in June 2014 that she had given £1,000,000 to the Better Together campaign.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the following month, whisky distiller William Grant & Sons announced a donation of approximately £100,000.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] On 12 August 2014, Better Together announced that it had raised enough money to cover the maximum spending permitted and was no longer accepting donations.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] This was attributed in part to a large number of small donations being received after the first televised debate between First Minister Alex Salmond and Labour MP Alistair Darling.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As of May 2014, the Yes Scotland campaign had declared £4,500,000 in cash donations.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] EuroMillions lottery-winners Chris and Colin Weir gave £3,500,000.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A six-figure donation was given by investment fund manager Angus Tulloch; approximately 18,000 donations of less than £7,500 had been made by the same date.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Voting for the referendum commenced on 27 August 2014, with the receipt of ballots by postal voters.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] As of 15 August, 680,235 eligible voters had registered for postal voting, a 20% increase compared with March 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] During the postal vote phase, Police Scotland arrested a man from Glasgow on suspicion of selling his vote on eBay.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The registration deadline for referendum voters was 2 September 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Several councils reported the processing of "unprecedented" numbers of new registrations, while others received "tens of thousands" of applications in the final week.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The UK Government said that, if a simple majority of the vote was in favour of independence, then 'Scotland would become an independent country after a process of negotiations'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] If the majority opposed independence, Scotland would remain part of the United Kingdom.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Further powers would be devolved to the Scottish Parliament as a result of the Scotland Act 2012.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] The Electoral Commission prepared an information leaflet which confirmed that the UK and Scottish governments had reached agreement on these points.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Cameron said in May 2014 that he believed that the referendum would be 'irreversible and binding'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the week before the referendum, both sides said they would abide by the result.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] Salmond said that it was a 'once in a generation' event, citing the precedent of the two devolution referendums in 1979 and 1997.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] In the event of a majority for Yes, the Scottish Government had proposed an independence date of 24 March 2016.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] It was suggested that, after negotiations concluded, the UK Parliament would legislate for Scottish independence to take place on the date that had been negotiated.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p01] A report by a UK House of Lords committee published in May 2014 said that the UK could opt to delay the independence date.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, as part of a European Union (EU) member state, Scottish farmers received £583 million in subsidy payments from the EU under the Common Agricultural Policy (CAP).
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Annual CAP payments are made to the UK, which then determines how much to allocate to each of the devolved administrations, including Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In the last CAP agreement, farmers in the UK qualified for additional convergence payments because Scottish farmers received a lower average single farm payment per hectare, mainly due to the mountainous terrain in Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Supporters of independence therefore believed that an independent Scotland would receive greater agricultural subsidies as an independent state.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Opponents of independence believed that Scottish farmers benefited from the Union because the UK was one of the larger EU member states, and therefore had a greater say in CAP negotiations.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] They also questioned whether an independent Scotland would immediately receive full subsidy payments from the EU, as recent new member states had their subsidies phased in.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At the time of the independence referendum, the UK had some opt-outs from EU policies.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] One was the opt-out from the Schengen Area, meaning there were full passport checks for travellers from other EU countries except the Republic of Ireland, which was part of a Common Travel Area (CTA) with the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government proposed that an independent Scotland would remain outside the Schengen Area and remain inside the CTA, ensuring that no passport controls would be needed at the Anglo-Scottish border.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Nicola Sturgeon commented that an independent Scotland would negotiate with the EU to have the same visa arrangements as the UK has.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Alistair Carmichael, the Secretary of State for Scotland, said in January 2014 that it would make sense for Scotland to be in the CTA, but it would have to operate similar immigration policies to the rest of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This position was supported by Home Secretary Theresa May, who said in March 2014 that passport checks should be introduced if Scotland adopted a looser immigration policy.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Conservative MP Richard Bacon said there would be "no reason" for border controls to be implemented.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In the white paper *Scotland's Future*, the Scottish government pledged to expand childcare provision in an independent Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The paper stated that this policy would cost £700 million, but that this would be financed by increased tax revenue from an additional 100,000 women returning to work.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In March 2014, the National Day Nurseries Association said that the plan could not be implemented unless greater funding was provided by local authorities to private nurseries.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A report by the Scottish Parliament Information Centre questioned the economic benefit of the policy, pointing out that there were only 64,000 mothers of children aged between 1 and 5 who were economically inactive.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government proposed that all British citizens who had been born in Scotland would automatically become Scottish citizens on the date of independence, regardless of whether or not they were then living in Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] British citizens "habitually resident" in Scotland would also be considered Scottish citizens, even if they already held the citizenship of another country.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Every person who would automatically be considered a Scottish citizen would be able to opt-out of Scottish citizenship provided they already held the citizenship of another country.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] UK Home Secretary Theresa May said the future policies of an independent Scottish government would affect whether Scottish citizens would be allowed to retain British citizenship.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] An analysis paper published by the UK government in January 2014 stated that it was likely that Scots would be able to hold dual citizenship; however, the duality was considered for all other countries, not specifically to the rest of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The possibility of holding dual UK–Scotland citizenships could be subject to the "proof of affinity".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A YouGov poll in early September showed 25 per cent of the electorate believed MI5 was working with the British government to block independence, with many voters so fearful that the marks made by the pencils provided in polling stations would be tampered with that they brought their own pens.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP said that there was a defence underspend of 'at least £7.4 billion' between 2002 and 2012 in Scotland and that independence would allow the Scottish government to correct this imbalance.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In its white paper, the Scottish government planned that an independent Scotland would have a total of 15,000 regular and 5,000 reserve personnel across land, air and maritime forces by 2026.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In July 2013, the SNP proposed that there would be a £2.5 billion annual military budget in an independent Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The House of Commons Defence Select Committee said that the £2.5bn budget was too low.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Andrew Murrison, UK Minister for International Security Strategy agreed and said it was 'risible' for the SNP to suggest it could create an independent force by 'salami-slicing' from current British armed forces units.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The House of Commons defence committee also stated that Scottish independence would have a negative effect on its industry, while the UK government said it would not be willing to build warships in a foreign country.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The chief executive of Thales, one of Britain's largest defence suppliers, said that if Scotland became independent that this might raise questions about continued investment from his firm.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Royal United Services Institute said in 2012 that an independent Scotland could set up a Scottish Defence Force, comparable in size and strength to those of other small European states like Denmark, Norway, and Ireland, at an annual cost of £1.8 billion.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Dorcha Lee, a former colonel in the Irish Army, said that Scotland could eschew forming an army based on inherited resources from the British Army and instead follow an Irish model of a limited self-defence force.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At the time of the referendum, the Trident nuclear missile system was based at Coulport weapons depot and naval base of Faslane in the Firth of Clyde area.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP objected to having nuclear weapons on Scottish territory, but British military leaders said that there was no alternative site for the missiles.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In April 2014, several British military leaders co-signed a letter stating that forcing Trident to leave Scottish waters would place the UK nuclear deterrent in jeopardy.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] *Nowhere to Go*, a report by Scottish CND, concluded that the removal of Trident from Scotland would force unilateral nuclear disarmament by the United Kingdom, as the weapons would have no viable alternative base.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A report by the Royal United Services Institute said that relocating Trident would be 'very difficult, but not impossible' and estimated it would take about 10 years and create an additional cost of around £3 billion.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] According to a seminar hosted by the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, that the Royal Navy would have to consider a range of alternatives, including disarmament.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A 2013 Scotland Institute report suggested a future Scottish government could be convinced to lease the Faslane nuclear base to the rest of the UK, in order to maintain good diplomatic relations and expedite NATO entry negotiations.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] SNP policy had historically been that an independent Scotland should not seek to obtain membership in NATO, but this was dropped after a vote by party members in 2012.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] MSPs John Finnie and Jean Urquhart resigned from the SNP over this policy change.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Green Party and Scottish Socialist Party continued their opposition to NATO membership.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP position that Trident nuclear weapons should be removed from Scotland but that it should hold NATO membership was criticised by Willie Rennie, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, and Patrick Harvie, co-convenor of the Scottish Green Party.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, Malcolm Chalmers of the Royal United Services Institute said that 'pragmatists' in the SNP accepted that NATO membership would likely involve a long-term basing deal, enabling the UK to keep Trident on the Clyde.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This was disputed by Mariot Leslie, a former UK permanent representative to NATO, who said that NATO would not want to disrupt its arrangements by excluding Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A UK government paper on security said that Police Scotland would lose access to the UK intelligence apparatus, including MI5, SIS, and GCHQ, and that an independent Scottish state would need to build security infrastructure.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Theresa May commented that an independent Scotland would have access to less security capability, but would not necessarily face a reduced threat.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] May also indicated that the British government would block Scotland from joining the Five Eyes intelligence-sharing alliance until Scotland had built up its own spying and intelligence infrastructure and was able to offer the alliance a "unique contribution".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, Allan Burnett, former head of intelligence with Strathclyde Police and Scotland's counter-terrorism coordinator until 2010, said that 'an independent Scotland would face less of a threat, intelligence institutions will be readily created, and allies will remain allies'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Baroness Ramsay, a Labour peer and former case officer with MI6, said that the Scottish government's stance on intelligence was 'extremely naïve' and that it was "not going to be as simple as they think".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Nicola Sturgeon said that Scotland would create a security service like MI5 to work alongside police and tackle terrorism, cyber-attacks and serious organised crime, and that creating an external intelligence agency would remain an option.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government and pro-independence campaigners said there was a democratic deficit in Scotland because the UK was a unitary state without a codified constitution.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP also called the unelected House of Lords an 'affront to democracy'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The 'democratic deficit' label has sometimes been used to refer to the period between the 1979 and 1997 UK general elections, during which the Labour Party held a majority of Scottish seats but the Conservative Party governed the whole of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond said in September 2013 that instances such as this amounted to a lack of democracy, and that 'people who live and work in Scotland are the people most likely to make the right choices for Scotland'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Menzies Campbell wrote in April 2014 that any democratic deficit had been addressed by creating the devolved Scottish Parliament, and that 'Scotland and the Scottish have enjoyed influence beyond our size or reasonable expectation' within the British government and the wider political system.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Conservative MP Daniel Kawczynski said in 2009 that the UK's asymmetric devolution had created a democratic deficit for England.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] This was commonly known as the West Lothian question, which cited the anomaly whereby English MPs could not vote on affairs devolved to Scotland but Scottish MPs could vote on the equivalent subjects in England.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Kawczynski also pointed out that the average number of voters in a parliamentary constituency was larger in England than in Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During the campaign, each of the three main UK parties conducted reviews of the UK constitution, with each recommending that more powers should devolve to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On the morning before a televised debate between Alex Salmond and Alistair Darling, Better Together published a joint statement.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Co-signed by the three main UK party leaders (David Cameron, Ed Miliband and Nick Clegg), it committed to granting Scotland increased power over domestic taxes and parts of the social security system.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Boris Johnson, the Conservative mayor of London, said he opposed giving the Scottish Parliament greater fiscal powers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During the second televised debate, Salmond challenged Darling to specify which additional powers that could help create greater employment in Scotland would be granted if there was a 'no' vote.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] During a visit to Scotland later that week, David Cameron promised more powers 'soon'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On 8 September, former Prime Minister Gordon Brown suggested a timetable for the additional powers to be implemented in the event of a 'no' vote.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He proposed that work on a new Scotland Act would begin immediately after the referendum, resulting in the publication of a white paper by the end of November 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Two days before the referendum, the three main UK party leaders publicly pledged to introduce 'extensive new powers' by the timetable suggested and that the Barnett formula of public funding would continue.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A principal issue in the referendum was the economy.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Weir Group, one of the largest private companies based in Scotland, commissioned a study by Oxford Economics into the potential economic effects of Scottish independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It found that Weir would pay more corporation tax, despite the Scottish government's proposal to cut the rate of corporation tax, due to it no longer being able to offset losses in Scotland against profits in the rest of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It also stated that independence would result in additional costs and complexity in the operation of business pension schemes.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report found that 70% of all Scottish exports are sold to the rest of the UK, which it said would particularly affect the financial services sector.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Standard Life, one of the Scottish financial sector's largest businesses, said in February 2014 that it had started registering companies in England in case it had to relocate some of its operations there.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In February 2014, the *Financial Times* noted that Scotland's per capita GDP was bigger than that of France when a geographic share of oil and gas was taken into account, and still bigger than that of Italy when it was not.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] As of April 2014, Scotland had a similar rate of unemployment to the UK average (6.6%) and a lower fiscal deficit (including as a percentage of GDP).
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Scotland performed better than the UK average in securing new Foreign Direct Investment in 2012–13 (measured by the number of projects), although not as well as Wales or Northern Ireland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] GDP growth during 2013 was lower in Scotland than in the rest of the UK, although this was partly due to an industrial dispute at the Grangemouth Refinery.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Deutsche Bank issued a report in the week before the referendum in which David Folkerts-Landau, the bank's chief economist, concluded: 'While it may sound simple and costless for a nation to exit a 300-year-old union, nothing could be further from the truth'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Folkerts-Landau said the economic prospects after a 'yes' vote were 'incomprehensible', and cited Winston Churchill's 1925 Gold Standard decision and the actions of America's Federal Reserve that triggered the Great Depression of the 1930s as mistakes of a similar magnitude.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Swiss financial services company UBS supported Deutsche Bank's position.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Supporters of independence said that Scotland had not realised its full economic potential because it was subject to the same economic policy as the rest of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2013, the Jimmy Reid Foundation published a report stating that UK economic policy had become 'overwhelmingly geared to helping London, meaning Scotland and other UK regions suffer from being denied the specific, local policies they need'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Later in January 2014, Colin Fox said that Scotland is 'penalised by an economic model biased towards the South East of England'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In November 2013, Chic Brodie said that Scotland was deprived of economic benefit in the 1980s after the Ministry of Defence blocked oil exploration off the West of Scotland, ostensibly to avoid interference with the UK's nuclear weapons arsenal.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The UK Treasury issued a report on 20 May 2013 which said that Scotland's banking systems would be too big to ensure depositor compensation in the event of a bank failure.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report indicated that Scottish banks would have assets worth 1,254% of GDP, which was more than Cyprus and Iceland before the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] It suggested Scottish taxpayers would each have £65,000 of potential liabilities during a hypothetical bailout in Scotland, versus £30,000 as part of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Economists including Andrew Hughes Hallett, Professor of Economics at St Andrews University, rejected the idea that Scotland would have to underwrite these liabilities alone.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He observed that banks operating in more than one country can be given a joint bailout by multiple governments.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In this way, France, Belgium, and the Netherlands collectively bailed out Fortis Bank and the Dexia Bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The American Federal Reserve System lent more than $1 trillion to British banks, including $446 billion to the Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS), because they had operations in the United States.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Robert Peston reported in March 2014 that RBS and Lloyds Banking Group might be forced to relocate their head offices from Edinburgh to London in case of Scottish independence, due to a European law brought in after the 1991 collapse of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Financial groups including RBS, Lloyds, Clydesdale Bank, TSB, and Tesco Bank later announced that they planned to move their registered headquarters from Scotland to England if Scotland voted for independence, although most indicated that they had no immediate intention to transfer any jobs.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Another major economic issue was the currency that an independent Scotland would use.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The principal options were to establish an independent Scottish currency, join the euro, or retain the pound sterling (a form of currency substitution).
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Throughout the 1990s and early 2000s, the SNP's policy was that an independent Scotland should adopt the euro, though this was relegated to a long-term rather than short-term goal by the party's 2009 conference.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] There was disagreement over whether Scotland would be required to join the euro if it became an EU member state in its own right.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] All new members are required to commit to joining the single currency, but they must first be party to ERM II for two years.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish government argued that this was a *de facto* opt-out from the euro, because EU member states are not obliged to join ERM II.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] For example, the people of Sweden rejected adopting the euro in a 2003 referendum and its government subsequently refused to enter ERM II.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The SNP favoured continued use of sterling in an independent Scotland through a formal currency union with the UK, with the Bank of England setting its interest rates and monetary policy and acting as its central bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In June 2012, Alistair Darling said voters in the rest of the UK could choose not to be in a currency union with Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Former Prime Minister Sir John Major rejected the idea of a currency union, saying it would require the UK to underwrite Scottish debt.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Former Prime Minister Gordon Brown said the SNP proposal would create a 'colonial relationship' between Scotland and Westminster.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Welsh First Minister Carwyn Jones said in November 2013 that he would seek a veto on a currency union between Scotland and the rest of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Yes Scotland said that a currency union would benefit both Scotland and the rest of the UK, as Scotland's exports would boost the balance of payments, and consequently strengthen the exchange rate of sterling.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Meanwhile, UK economists and financial experts said the effect on the balance of payments and the exchange rate would be 'largely neutral'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Sterling fell by almost one cent against the US dollar in a day early in September 2014, due to an opinion poll showing a swing towards the Yes campaign.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The *Financial Times* reported a few days later that 'Asset managers, investors and pension savers are moving billions of pounds out of Scotland' because of fears that Scotland would leave the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The newspaper also reported that '"exit clauses" are being inserted into commercial property contracts in Scotland to allow buyers to scrap deals or renegotiate prices if voters opt for independence'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Scottish Labour leader Johann Lamont said that any additional transaction costs would fall largely on Scottish companies, costing businesses in Scotland 11 times more than those in England.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Institute of Directors said that any new transaction costs would 'pale in comparison to the financial danger of entering an unstable currency union'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Banking experts said that being the 'junior partner' in a currency arrangement could amount to 'a loss of fiscal autonomy for Scotland' if policy constraints were imposed on the Scottish state.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Angus Armstrong of the National Institute of Economic and Social Research wrote that the implicit constraints on its economic policy would be more restrictive than the explicit ones it faced as part of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond said in February 2014 that an independent Scotland in a currency union would retain tax and spending powers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The UK Chancellor George Osborne, as well as equivalent post-holders in the two other main UK political parties, rejected the idea of a formal currency union with an independent Scotland in February 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Shadow Chancellor Ed Balls said the SNP's proposals for a currency union were 'economically incoherent' and that any currency option for an independent Scotland would be 'less advantageous than what we have across the UK today'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] After the three main UK political parties ruled out a formal currency union, the Adam Smith Institute said that the economies of Panama, Ecuador, and El Salvador 'demonstrate that the informal use of another country's currency can foster a healthy financial system and economy'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In September 2014, former European Commissioner Olli Rehn said that an independent Scotland would be unable to meet EU membership requirements if it shared sterling informally, as it would not have an independent central bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Salmond disputed this, restating his belief that a sterling currency union would be formed and pledging to create the necessary financial institutions.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Socialist Party favoured an independent Scottish currency, pegged to sterling in the short term.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Scottish Green Party said that keeping sterling as 'a short term transitional arrangement' should not be ruled out, but also that the Scottish Government should 'keep an open mind about moving towards an independent currency'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In early 2013, the Jimmy Reid Foundation described retention of the pound as a good transitional arrangement, but recommended the eventual establishment of an independent Scottish currency to 'insulate' Scotland from the UK's 'economic instability'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Other proponents of an independent Scottish currency included Yes Scotland chairman Dennis Canavan and former SNP deputy leader Jim Sillars.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] On 9 September 2014, Mark Carney, governor of the Bank of England, said that a currency union between an independent Scotland and the remainder of the UK would be 'incompatible with sovereignty'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] He added that cross-border ties on tax, spending and banking rules are a prerequisite: 'You only have to look across the continent to look at what happens if you don't have those components in place ...
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] At present under devolution, Scotland controls only 7% of our revenues.' Carney's comments received vocal support from Darling and the GMB trade union.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Barnett formula, introduced in the late 1970s, had resulted in higher per-capita public spending in Scotland than England.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] If an allocation of North Sea oil revenue based on geography was included, Scotland also produced more per capita tax revenue than the UK average in the years immediately preceding the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Institute for Fiscal Studies reported in November 2012 that a geographic share of North Sea oil would more than cover the higher public spending, but warned that oil prices are volatile and that they are drawn from a finite resource.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The Government Expenditure and Revenue Scotland report for 2012/13 found that North Sea oil revenue had fallen by 41.5% and that Scotland's public spending deficit had increased from £4.6 billion to £8.6 billion.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] In 2012, the Scottish Government's Finance Secretary John Swinney prepared a confidential cabinet briefing paper on the financial impact of Scottish independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report warned that an independent Scotland would face public spending cuts, lower pensions and welfare spending, and high levels of debt.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report warned that Scotland's public finances would be heavily dependent on volatile and declining oil revenues, and suggested that the affordability of the state pension in an independent Scotland would be at risk.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] The report further warned that the SNP's plans for an oil fund under independence would "require some downward revision in current spending." Swinney's cabinet paper was kept secret before being leaked to the press in 2013, a year after it was drafted.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] Alistair Darling, the leader of the Better Together campaign opposed to Scottish independence, described the leaked report as a "hammer blow" to the SNP's economic credibility.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p02] A Scottish Government spokesman insisted that the report's findings had been "overtaken by events".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In May 2014, the UK government published an analysis identifying a 'Union dividend' of £1,400 per year for each person in Scotland, mainly due to the higher level of public spending.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government disputed this analysis, saying that each Scot would be £1,000 better off per year under independence by 2030.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Three economic experts said that both estimates were possible, but they depended on unknown variables such as the division of UK government debt, future North Sea oil revenues, possible spending commitments of an independent Scotland and future productivity gains.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In its analysis, the UK government also estimated setup costs of £1.5 billion (1% of GDP) for establishing an independent state, or possibly £2.7 billion (180 public bodies costing £15 million each).
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Patrick Dunleavy of the London School of Economics criticised the UK government's 'ludicrous' use of his research in arriving at the latter figure.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Treasury said that their main figure (£1.5 billion) was based on estimates by Robert Young of Western University.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Two of the main unionist parties in Scotland called on the SNP to publish their own estimate of the setup costs of an independent state, but the Scottish government said that an estimate was not possible as the final bill would depend on negotiations with the rest of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Dunleavy estimated immediate setup costs of £200 million in a report commissioned by *The Sunday Post*, with 'total transition costs' of between £600 million and £1,500 million in the first 10 years of independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The credit rating that an independent Scotland would merit also became a subject of debate.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The credit-rating agency Fitch said in 2012 that it could not give an opinion on what rating Scotland would have, because Scottish finances would largely depend on the result of negotiations between the UK and Scotland and specifically the division of UK assets and liabilities.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Research published by Moody's in May 2014 said that an independent Scotland would be given an A rating, comparable with Poland, the Czech Republic and Mexico.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] An A rating would have been two grades below its then rating for the UK, which Moody's said would be unaffected by Scottish independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The UK government controlled most energy issues, although control over planning laws had allowed the Scottish government to prevent the construction of new nuclear power stations in Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence wanted to retain a single energy market for the whole of Great Britain after independence, to maintain price stability and support for suppliers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents said that independence would threaten that single energy market.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Euan Phimister, professor of economics at Aberdeen University, said that although independence would affect the relationship, it was likely that there would be continued English demand for electricity generated in Scotland due to the lack of spare capacity elsewhere.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The second largest supplier of energy in the UK, SSE plc, believed that a single market would be the most likely outcome under independence, although it would require negotiations that may have led to changes to the existing system.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour MP Caroline Flint said that independence would mean higher energy bills in Scotland, as its customers would have to pay more to support renewable energy in Scotland, which represented one-third of the UK total.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Euan Phimister said that bills were likely to increase across the whole of Great Britain because renewable schemes and new nuclear power stations in England were receiving higher subsidies than the power plants which were due for closure due to environmental regulations.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He also said that there was a distinction between existing and proposed renewable schemes in that the existing schemes had already been paid for, whereas any new construction required the promise of subsidy from the consumer.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Energy and Climate Change Secretary Ed Davey said Scottish generators would no longer be eligible for UK subsidies, which would increase energy bills for consumers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Approximately 90% of the United Kingdom's North Sea oil fields were located in Scottish territorial waters.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The tax revenue generated from an offshore site was not counted within the nation or region nearest to it, but was instead allocated to the UK Continental Shelf.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The revenue from North Sea oil was used to support current expenditure, and the UK did not create a sovereign oil fund (as in Norway).
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP believed that a portion of the revenues should have been invested in a sovereign oil fund.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government, citing industry body Oil and Gas UK, estimated in *Scotland's Future* that there were 24 billion barrels of oil equivalent still to be extracted.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir Ian Wood, founder of oil services company Wood Group, said in August 2014 that he believed there were between 15 and 16.5 billion boe and that the impact from declining production would be felt by 2030.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2014, an investigation by industry recruitment website *Oil and Gas People* found that there were extensive oil reserves to the west of the Western Isles and Shetland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The report anticipated that the region would be developed within the next 10 years because of improvements in drilling technology, rig design and surveying.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP advocated that an independent Scotland should become a full member state of the European Union (EU) with some exemptions, such as not having to adopt the euro.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was debate over whether Scotland would be required to reapply for membership and whether it could retain the UK's opt-outs.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The European Commission (EC) offered to provide an opinion to an existing member state on the matter, but the UK government confirmed it would not seek this advice, as it did not want to negotiate the terms of independence in advance of the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was no precedent for an EU member state dividing into two sovereign countries after joining the EU.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence stated that an independent Scotland would become an EU member by treaty amendment under Article 48 of the EU treaties.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents said that this would not be possible and that an independent Scotland would need to apply for EU membership under Article 49, which would require ratification by each member state.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, Christina McKelvie, Convener of the European and External Relations Committee of the Scottish Parliament, asked Viviane Reding, Vice-President of the European Commission, whether Article 48 would apply.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Reding replied that EU treaties would no longer apply to a territory that secedes from a member state.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] She also said that Article 49 would be the route to apply to become a member of the EU.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] José Manuel Barroso, president of the European Commission, said earlier that an independent Scotland would have to apply for EU membership, while the rest of the UK would continue to be a member.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In 2014, he reiterated that for Scotland to join the EU would be 'extremely difficult, if not impossible'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former prime minister Sir John Major suggested in November 2013 that Scotland would need to reapply for EU membership, but that this would mean overcoming opposition to separatism among other member states.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Salmond cited a letter from Mario Tenreiro of the EC's secretariat general that said it would be legally possible to renegotiate the situation of the UK and Scotland within the EU by unanimous agreement of all member states.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Spain's European Affairs minister reiterated their position two days before the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir David Edward, a former European Court judge, said that the EU institutions and member states would be 'obliged' to start negotiations before independence took effect to decide the future relationship.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He said this would be achieved by agreed amendment of the existing Treaties (Article 48), rather than a new Accession Treaty (Article 49).
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Graham Avery, the EC's honorary director-general, agreed with Edward.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Avery wrote a report, published by the European Policy Centre, which said that EU leaders would probably allow Scotland to be part of the EU because of the legal and practical difficulties that would arise from excluding it.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In a research paper, Professor Sionaidh Douglas-Scott of Oxford University wrote that the EU law normally takes a 'pragmatic and purposive approach' to issues not already provided for by existing treaties.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In January 2013, the Republic of Ireland's Minister of European Affairs, Lucinda Creighton, said that if Scotland were to become independent, it 'would have to apply for membership and that can be a lengthy process'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] She later clarified those remarks, writing that she 'certainly did not at any stage suggest that Scotland could, should or would be thrown out of the EU'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He also said that Barroso's comments on the legal position had 'no basis in the European treaties'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In January 2013, David Cameron committed the Conservative Party to a referendum before the end of 2017 on UK membership of the EU if they won the 2015 general election.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Legislation for an in/out EU referendum was approved by the House of Commons in November 2013.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Studies showed some divergence in attitudes to the EU in Scotland and the rest of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In contrast, there was a majority for withdrawal in England.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Yes Scotland said that the UK government plans for an EU referendum had caused "economic uncertainty" for Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During a CBI Scotland event attended by Cameron, businessman Michael Rake criticised him for creating uncertainty about EU membership.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In response to such criticism, Cameron pointed to examples of inward investment in the UK that he said was not happening in the rest of Europe.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some commentators suggested that the UK leaving the EU could undermine the case for Scottish independence, since free trade, freedom of movement and the absence of border controls between Scotland and England could no longer be assumed.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Responsibility for most aspects of health care was devolved to the Scottish Parliament when it was established in 1999.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government enacted health policies which were different from those in England, such as abolishing charges for prescriptions and elderly personal care.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] NHS Scotland was operationally independent of the NHS in the rest of the United Kingdom since the formation of the NHS in 1948.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Supporters of independence argued that independence was needed because possible reductions in the NHS budget in England would result in reduced funding for Scotland, which would make it difficult to maintain the existing service.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Harry Burns, a former chief medical officer for Scotland, said in July 2014 that he thought independence could be beneficial for public health because it may give people greater control of their lives.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In May 2014, about 100 medical workers, including surgeons, consultant doctors, GPs, pharmacists, dentists, hospital porters and janitors joined a pro-independence campaign group called "NHS for Yes".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In contrast, opponents argued that a subsequent drop in funding to an independent Scottish Government would have a significantly larger effect upon the budget.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Concerns were also raised about the impact on the medical research sector in Scotland from the loss of UK wide research funding.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Two days before the referendum, papers indicating "a funding gap of £400–£450m in the next two financial years, 2015–17", for Scotland's NHS, resulting from Scottish government policies, were leaked to the media.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A Scottish government spokesperson commented that the papers were from "part of the regular discussions among NHS leaders to plan for NHS Scotland's future".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Opponents of independence said that being part of the UK was crucial in allowing Scots to obtain specialist treatment elsewhere in the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Although operationally independent, NHS Scotland had reciprocal arrangements in place with the NHS services in the rest of the UK and specialist services were shared.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Vote No Borders, a unionist campaign group, ran a cinema advert which claimed that Scots would find it more difficult to obtain treatment at the Great Ormond Street Hospital (GOSH), a London facility which provided specialist care for children.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Vote No Borders withdrew the advert after GOSH complained that it had not been consulted about the advert and stated that they had reciprocal health care agreements with numerous countries.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The white paper on independence proposed that an independent Scotland would open around 100 embassies around the world.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Prime Minister David Cameron suggested that an independent Scotland would be "marginalised" at the United Nations, where the UK is a permanent member of the Security Council.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former Prime Minister John Major suggested that the UK could lose its permanent seat at the Security Council if Scotland became independent.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Forming a republic was favoured by some pro-independence political parties and organisations, including the Scottish Green Party and the Scottish Socialist Party.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP favoured an independent Scotland continuing to recognise Elizabeth II as Queen of Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Christine Grahame MSP said she believed that party policy was to hold a referendum on the matter, due to a 1997 SNP conference resolution.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some media reports suggested that the announcement on 8 September of the pregnancy of the Duchess of Cambridge with her second child would help pro-union sentiment.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Queen's official position on Scottish independence was neutral.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Just prior to the referendum, Elizabeth II said in a private conversation that she hoped people would "think very carefully about the future".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UK State Pensions were managed by the UK government, paying £113.10 per week to a single person who is of state pension age in the 2013/14 tax year.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The state pension age for men was 65, but this was due to rise to 66 in 2020 and 67 by 2028.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Research by the National Institute of Economic and Social Research found that an independent Scotland could delay these increases, due to a lower life expectancy.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The *Scotland's Future* white paper pledged to maintain a state pension at a similar rate to the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former UK Prime Minister Gordon Brown said in April 2014 that Scotland had an above-average share of the public-sector pension bill and concluded that pensions would be protected by sharing risks and resources within the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UK government pensions minister Steve Webb said in May 2014 that Scots would be entitled to the current levels of state pension after independence because they had accumulated rights within the existing system.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Webb went on to say that there would need to be negotiations between the UK and Scotland as to how these pensions would be paid.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In relation to private pension schemes, a report by the Institute of Chartered Accountants of Scotland expressed concern that there were no plans to deal with EU regulations that may affect the funding of cross-border defined benefit schemes.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The EC decided in March 2014 not to relax these regulations, which require cross-border schemes to be fully funded.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scotland hosted the 2014 Commonwealth Games in Glasgow, less than two months before the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish team won a record number of gold medals, which the writer Alan Bisset said would help give voters more belief and confidence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *Sunday Herald* columnist Ian Bell took an opposing view, saying that sporting success would be unlikely to aid support for independence, due to the lengthy and passionate debate on the subject.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former Labour first minister Henry McLeish published a report in May 2014 that found no obvious barriers to an independent Scotland competing in the 2016 Summer Olympics.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] McLeish said that some athletes, particularly those in team sports, may choose to compete for the existing Great Britain team rather than Scotland, as they would be nationals of both states.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Gordon Brown pointed to the 2012 medal count for Great Britain, saying that it showed the success of the union.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scottish athletes were involved in 13 of the 65 medals won by Great Britain in 2012, but only three of those were won without assistance by athletes from other parts of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Sir Chris Hoy said in May 2013 that it would "take time" for Scottish athletes to "establish themselves in a new training environment", and indicated that the good performance of Scottish athletes in the Great Britain team would not automatically translate into that of an independent Scotland team.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Hoy also said that he believed the lack of facilities and coaching infrastructure in Scotland would have to be addressed by an independent state.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The prospect of an independent Scotland raised questions about the future of the Northern Isles (Orkney and Shetland) and the Western Isles, island groups off the Scottish mainland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Some islanders called for separate referendums to be held in the islands on 25 September 2014, one week after the Scottish referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, the Scottish Parliament published an online petition it had received calling for such referendums, which was supported by Shetland MSP Tavish Scott.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The proposed referendums would have asked islanders to choose from three options: that the island group should become an independent country; that it should remain in Scotland; or that (in the event of Scottish independence) it should remain in the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The third option would have implemented a conditional promise made in 2012 by an SNP spokesperson, who said that Orkney and Shetland could remain in the United Kingdom if their "drive for self-determination" was strong enough.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Politicians in the three island groups referred to the Scottish referendum as the most important event in their political history "since the inception of the island councils in 1975".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Angus Campbell, leader of the Western Isles, said that the ongoing constitutional debate offered the "opportunity for the three island councils to secure increased powers for our communities to take decisions which will benefit the economies and the lives of those who live in the islands".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In a meeting of the island councils in March 2013, leaders of the three territories discussed their future in the event of Scottish independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] This included whether the islands could demand and achieve autonomous status within either Scotland or the rest of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Among the scenarios proposed were achieving either Crown Dependency status or self-government modelled after the Faroe Islands, in association with either Scotland or the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Steven Heddle, Orkney's council leader, described pursuing Crown Dependency status as the least likely option, as it would threaten funding from the EU, which was essential for local farmers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alasdair Allan, MSP for the Western Isles, said independence could have a positive impact on the isles, as "crofters and farmers could expect a substantial uplift in agricultural and rural development funding via the Common Agricultural Policy if Scotland were an independent member state of the EU".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In July 2013, the Scottish government made the Lerwick Declaration, indicating an interest in devolving power to Scotland's islands.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] By November, it had committed to devolving further powers to Orkney, Shetland and the Western Isles in the event of independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Steven Heddle called for legislation to that effect to be introduced regardless of the referendum result.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He stated that he did not want such circumstances to arise, "and the best way to avoid this was to vote no in the referendum".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In 2012–13, Scottish universities received 13.1% of Research Councils UK funding.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alan Trench of University College London said that Scottish universities had received a "hugely disproportionate" level of funding and would no longer be able to access it following independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Willie Rennie, leader of the Scottish Liberal Democrats, suggested that independence would mean Scottish universities losing £210m in research funding.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Institute of Physics in Scotland warned that access to international facilities such as the CERN Large Hadron Collider, the European Space Agency, and European Southern Observatory could require renegotiation by the Scottish government.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It also expressed concerns about research funding from UK charities and the reaction of international companies with Scottish facilities.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government's education secretary, Michael Russell, said that Scotland's universities had a "global reputation" that would continue to attract investment after independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2013, the principal of the University of Aberdeen said that Scottish universities could continue to access UK research funding through a "single research area" that crossed both nations' boundaries.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] David Bell, professor of economics at the University of Stirling, said that cross-border collaboration might continue, but Scottish universities could still lose their financial advantage.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Roger Cook of the Scotland Institute pointed out that although Scottish universities had received a higher share of Research Councils funding, they were much less dependent on this as a source of funding than their counterparts in England.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professors from Scotland's five medical schools wrote an open letter warning that independence would mean Scotland's researcher base being "denied its present ability to win proportionately more grant funding".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Questions were asked whether Scotland, as an economy of a smaller size than the UK, would still support the same level of research activity, and what additional efforts might be required to establish a system of research councils "north of the border".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Jo Shaw, Salvesen chair of European institutions at the University of Edinburgh, noted that in smaller states, relationships between universities and research funders became "cosy", and led to a "corporatist" approach.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the time of the referendum, Students domiciled in Scotland did not pay tuition fees.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Students domiciled in the rest of the UK were charged fees of up to £9,000 per annum by Scottish universities, but those from other EU member states were not charged fees due to EU law.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] If Scotland had become an independent state, students from the rest of the UK would have been in the same position as students from the rest of the EU.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A University of Edinburgh study found that this would cause a loss in funding, which could have squeezed out Scottish students.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It concluded that the EU may allow a quota system for some specialist subjects, such as medicine, where there was a clear need for local students to be trained for particular careers, but that other subjects would not be eligible.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The study also found that their third suggestion would run against the spirit of the Bologna agreement, which aimed to encourage EU student mobility.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish government stated in its white paper, *Scotland's Future*, that the present tuition fees arrangement would remain in place in an independent Scotland, as the EU allowed for different fee arrangements in "exceptional circumstances".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Ján Figeľ, a former EU commissioner for education, said in January 2014 that it would be illegal for an independent Scotland to apply a different treatment to students from the rest of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A report by a House of Commons select committee stated that it would cost an independent Scottish government £150 million to provide free tuition to students from the rest of the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A group of academics campaigning for independence expressed concern that the present arrangements would not continue if Scotland stayed within the UK, due to public spending cuts in England and the consequential effects of the Barnett formula.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Yes campaign argued that control of welfare policy would be a major benefit of independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] According to the Institute for Fiscal Studies, independence would "give the opportunity for more radical reform, so that the [welfare] system better reflects the views of the Scottish people".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Yes Scotland and deputy first minister Nicola Sturgeon said the existing welfare system could only be guaranteed by voting for independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In September 2013, the Scottish Council for Voluntary Organisations (SCVO), which represents charities, called for a separate welfare system to be established in Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In November 2013, the Scottish government pledged to use the powers of independence to reverse key aspects of the Welfare Reform Act 2012, which was implemented across the UK despite opposition from a majority of Scotland's MPs.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It said it would abolish Universal Credit and the bedroom tax.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The SNP also criticised Rachel Reeves, Labour's shadow secretary of state for work and pensions, for saying that a future UK Labour government would be even tougher on benefits than the Cameron–Clegg coalition government.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour politician Jim Murphy, a former Secretary of State for Scotland, said that he was "fiercely committed" to devolving welfare powers to the Scottish Parliament, but also warned that independence would be disruptive and would not be beneficial.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Scottish Labour's Devolution Commission recommended in March 2014 that some aspects of the welfare state, including housing benefit and attendance allowance, should be devolved.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Feminist economist Ailsa McKay, a supporter of the Radical Independence movement, argued that an independent Scotland should change its welfare system dramatically by offering all its people a basic income.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A number of demonstrations in support of independence were co-ordinated following the announcement of the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The March and Rally for Scottish Independence in September 2012 drew a crowd of between 5,000 and 10,000 people to Princes Street Gardens.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The event was repeated in September 2013; police estimated that over 8,000 people took part in the march, while organisers and the Scottish Police Federation claimed between 20,000 and 30,000 people took part in the combined march and rally.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The March and Rally was criticised in both 2012 and 2013 for the involvement of groups like the Scottish Republican Socialist Movement and Vlaamse Volksbeweging.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Five days before the referendum vote, the Orange Order – a Protestant brotherhood – held a major anti-independence march and rally in Edinburgh.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] It involved at least 15,000 Orangemen, loyalist bands and supporters from Scotland and across the UK, and was described as the biggest pro-Union demonstration of the campaign up to that date.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A rally for UK unity, organised by the Let's Stay Together campaign, was attended by 5,000 people in London's Trafalgar Square on the Monday preceding the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Similar events were held in London, Bristol, Leeds, Cardiff, Manchester and Belfast on the day before the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Labour MP Jim Murphy conducted a Scotland-wide tour to campaign for the No side, intending to visit 100 towns and cities in 100 days before the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 28 August he suspended his tour, after being hit by an egg in Kirkcaldy, and it was resumed on 3 September.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Murphy said that he had been subjected to "co-ordinated abuse" from Yes supporters and pointed to evidence of this on social media.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Better Together released footage of events in the tour where he was heckled by members of the public, some of whom called him a "traitor", "parasite", "terrorist" and "quisling".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] David Cameron said that "there's nothing wrong with a bit of heckling, but throwing things isn't necessarily part of the democratic process".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alex Salmond pointed out that people had "every entitlement to peaceful protest", but also said that "people shouldn't throw eggs at somebody full stop".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the launch of the Yes Scotland campaign in May 2012, Alex Salmond said that the case for independence would be driven by community activism and "online wizardry".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The not-for-profit and non-partisan *What Scotland Thinks* project tracked poll and survey data, including online activity, during the referendum campaign.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Using data from the Applied Quantitative Methods Network (AQMeN) research centre, the project compiled the social media activity of the two main campaigns, Yes Scotland and Better Together, by monitoring their respective Facebook and Twitter accounts since August 2013.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *What Scotland Thinks* published a report in February 2014 stating that the Yes Scotland campaign was gaining more Facebook likes.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Following the launch of the White Paper on 26 November, the average gap between the two Facebook pages grew from about 8,000 to about 23,000 by February 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Analysis of the campaigns' Twitter accounts showed the gap between the campaigns increased from approximately 8,000 followers in August 2013 to 13,804 followers in February 2014, in favour of Yes Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The project published a further report in June 2014 saying that greater online activity for Yes Scotland had continued.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professor Michael Keating said in April 2014 that the pro-independence movement was visibly stronger and fighting a "ground war", while unionist supporters were fighting an "'air war' of facts and figures".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The launch of online celebrity videos from both viewpoints was reported by the media in mid-July 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The "Let's Stay Together" campaign group produced a YouTube video called "'Scotland, you're my best friend'", featuring John Barrowman, Ross Kemp and Eddie Izzard.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A pro-independence video was produced by Yes Scotland and appeared on the campaign's YouTube channel.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Titled "✘ on September 18th #voteYes", the video features 32 people, including David Hayman, Martin Compston and Stuart Braithwaite.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The pro-independence organisation National Collective was identified by the *Independent* newspaper as the initiators of an online hashtag campaign that began in mid-August 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Writing for the *Independent*, Antonia Molloy said that the previous "#IndyReasons" hashtag campaign served as the inspiration for the "#YesBecause" campaign that was observed on the Twitter, Facebook and Vine social media platforms.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] From 21 August, users were invited to explain their reasons for voting "Yes" and #YesBecause was trending on Twitter after an hour from the launch.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) reported on 22 August that a "#NoBecause" campaign emerged in opposition to the Collective.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Debates over the issue of independence took place on television, in communities, and within universities and societies since the announcement of the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The STV current affairs programme *Scotland Tonight* televised a series of debates: Nicola Sturgeon v Michael Moore, Sturgeon v Anas Sarwar, Sturgeon v Alistair Carmichael and Sturgeon v Johann Lamont.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 21 January 2014, BBC Two Scotland broadcast the first in a series of round-table debates, which was filmed in Greenock and chaired by James Cook.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Yes campaign repeatedly called for a televised debate between UK Prime Minister David Cameron and First Minister of Scotland Alex Salmond.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] These calls for a one-on-one debate were dismissed by Cameron on the basis that the referendum is "for Scots to decide" and the debate should be "between people in Scotland who want to stay, and people in Scotland who want to go".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Calls for such a debate were also supported by former Prime Minister Gordon Brown who said it would be a "good idea".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Better Together chairman Alistair Darling accused Salmond of "running scared" from debating him instead, although Sturgeon stated in 2013 that a Salmond–Darling debate would take place at some point.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Darling refused a public debate with Yes Scotland chairman Blair Jenkins.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] UKIP leader Nigel Farage also challenged Salmond to debate, but Farage was dismissed by an SNP spokeswoman as "an irrelevance in Scotland".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] After weeks of negotiation, a debate between Salmond and Darling was arranged.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The programme, titled as *Salmond & Darling: The Debate*, was broadcast by STV on 5 August 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The debate, moderated by Bernard Ponsonby, saw both politicians make opening statements and cross-examine each other before taking questions from the audience.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] At the end of the clash, they were both given the chance to make a closing speech.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Both campaign groups claimed victory in the debate.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A snap poll conducted by ICM stated Darling won the debate by 56% to 44%.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In his analysis of the ICM poll, Professor John Curtice detected little movement either way as a result of the debate.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A second debate between Salmond and Darling, titled *Scotland Decides: Salmond versus Darling* was shown on BBC One Scotland (and BBC Two in the rest of the UK) on 25 August, and was hosted by Glenn Campbell.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Salmond was perceived to have won the debate, and a snap poll conducted by ICM Research stated Salmond won the debate by 71% to 29%.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2014, BBC Scotland chiefs appeared before a Scottish Parliament committee to face questions from MSPs about the broadcaster's coverage.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During that session, BBC Scotland director Ken MacQuarrie disputed the findings of Robertson's study, saying that its conclusions were largely based upon "flawed analysis" and had contained factual errors.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] During the latter stages of the campaign there were further allegations by some independence supporters that the BBC – the UK's national broadcaster – was biased against Scottish independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In an interview for the *Sunday Herald*, Alex Salmond said he believed the BBC had been unconsciously biased against independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Former BBC journalist Paul Mason commented: "Not since Iraq have I seen BBC News working at propaganda strength like this".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The BBC replied that "Our coverage of the referendum story is fair and impartial in line with the editorial guidelines".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alex Massie wrote in *The Spectator* that the BBC's coverage was consistent with their attitude towards other government proposals of such magnitude and that it was incumbent upon the Yes campaign to prove its assertions.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 29 June, several hundred independence supporters gathered in a demonstration outside BBC Pacific Quay, the main BBC studio in Glasgow, in protest at its alleged bias.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A week before the vote, BBC political editor Nick Robinson said in a news item that Salmond "didn't answer" his questions at a press conference.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Several thousand independence supporters then protested at the BBC Scotland headquarters, accusing the BBC of broadcasting pro-Union "propaganda" and "lies".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] *The Independent* reported that the protesters accused Robinson of working "with the Treasury to spread lies about the dangers to business and financial services of an independent Scotland".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Alastair Campbell said that the "organised protests" amounted to media censorship "not far off" Vladimir Putin's Russia, telling Twitter users they should "Vote YES for intimidation".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The National Union of Journalists (NUJ) asked people to think about the implications of alleging journalistic bias when its members were only asking difficult questions.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Robinson later expressed his "regret" at using the phrase "didn't answer" in his report and criticised the protests.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Speaking after the referendum, Yes Scotland chief executive Blair Jenkins said that he did not believe there was a "systemic bias" against Yes or any "corporate intent to disadvantage the Yes campaign".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In addition to the incidents described above, there were reports of intimidation during the campaign.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] A survey of the 133 business leaders who signed a public letter backing the Union reported that half of respondents "said that they had felt intimidated or pressurised by SNP or the Yes campaign as a result of their views".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The *Daily Telegraph* reported that other businesspeople had been unwilling to express an opinion on the referendum publicly because they were concerned about a loss of business from the SNP-led Scottish government or local government.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The NUJ called for abuse and bullying of its members, which had been led by online attacks, to end, commenting that, "For the duration of the referendum there has been hostility to journalists doing their jobs".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish Police Federation stated that criminal acts related to the referendum were few in number and criticised those "suggesting a minority of mindless idiots are representative of anything".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Professor John Curtice stated in January 2012 that polling showed support for independence at 32%–38% of the Scottish population, which represented a slight decline from 2007, when the SNP had first formed the Scottish government.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] By 2012, there had been no poll evidence of majority support for independence, although the share "vehemently opposed to independence" had declined.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] According to Curtice, the polls were stable during most of 2013, with "no" leading by an average of 17% with a year to go.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Polling expert Nate Silver said in 2013 that the yes campaign had "virtually no chance" of winning the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] After the referendum, Silver said that although his prediction had been proven "right" he had done little research beforehand.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The gap narrowed after the release of the Scottish government white paper on independence: an average of five polls in December 2013 and January 2014 gave 39% yes and 61% no, once 'don't knows' had been excluded.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The polls tightened further after the Chancellor of the Exchequer, George Osborne, stated in February that the UK government was opposed to a currency union; the average yes support increased to 43%, once 'don't knows' had been excluded.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] There was little movement in the following months, with the average continuing to show 43% yes and 57% no (excluding don't knows) in July 2014 and August 2014.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In early September, polls indicated that the vote would be closer than had been indicated earlier.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] On 6 September a YouGov poll gave those in favour 47% versus 45% for those against; excluding those undecided, the figures were 51% and 49%, respectively.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The final polls, taken in the last few days of the campaign, indicated a lead for No of between 4% and 6%.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Soon after polling stations had closed, YouGov released a final poll that had been taken during the day of voting, indicating 46% Yes, 54% No.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Writing after the referendum, Nate Silver pointed out that the final margin of victory for No was greater than that indicated by the opinion polls.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] He suggested that this could have been due to less enthusiastic voters being more pro-Union, which may not have been reflected in the polls.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Stephen Fisher, a sociology professor at Oxford University, noted in a study of other constitutional referendums that pollsters had tended to overestimate the "Yes" option.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] In March 2015, a poll carried out by YouGov found a slight majority of support for independence among people born in Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The Scottish Independence Referendum Bill identified the convener of the Electoral Management Board for Scotland as chief counting officer for the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] The chief counting officer, Mary Pitcaithly, was supported by a counting officer in each of the 32 local authority areas of Scotland, who was typically the chief executive for that local authority.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Voting took place between 07:00 and 22:00 BST in "polling places", which included schools, church halls, libraries and community centres.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Those who were still queuing when polls closed were not denied the chance to vote.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Votes from the 32 local government areas were counted and announced by each area separately.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p03] Results came in during the early hours of 19 September, with the first result being from Clackmannanshire, and the last being from Highland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] 55.3% voted against independence, with a turnout of 84.6%.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] 28 of the 32 council areas voted "No", although the four areas that voted "Yes" (Dundee, Glasgow, North Lanarkshire and West Dunbartonshire) contained over 20% of the Scottish electorate.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The overall turnout of 84.6% was very high for Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Turnout was around 50–60% for elections to the Scottish and UK parliaments in the early 21st century.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The most recent United Kingdom general election with a comparable turnout was in 1950, when 83.9% voted.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The last ballot in the United Kingdom with a higher turnout than 84.6% was in January 1910, when no women and fewer men were allowed to vote (i.e., before universal suffrage applied to UK elections).
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Of the 32 areas, East Dunbartonshire had the highest turnout at 91.0%, and Glasgow the lowest at 75.0%.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An academic study, surveying 5,000 Scottish voters soon after the referendum, found that the majority for No was formed by an "unusual alliance" of the very young, average earners, Protestants and women.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The study supported polling evidence that there was a gender gap, but countered beliefs that higher earners had supported No and that younger voters had mostly voted Yes.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] According to John Curtice, polling evidence indicates that support for independence was highest among those aged in their late 20s and early 30s, with a higher No vote among those aged between 16 and 24.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] There was an age gap at the referendum, with elderly voters being the most likely to vote against independence and younger voters aged under 55, except for those aged between 16 and 24, generally being more in favour of independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This was picked up by other academics, with data from the Scottish Index of Multiple Deprivation study from 2012 indicating that the six most deprived local authorities in Scotland returned the highest Yes vote shares at the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This is an incomplete list as not all local authorities counted by ward or constituency.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The constituency results are primarily obtained through local authority breakdowns of the result or the constituency boundaries being co-terminous with the local government district.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the day of the referendum, Michael Ashcroft conducted a poll of over 2,000 voters to identify the major reasons for their voting choices.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This poll found that among No voters, more than half (57%) stated the pound sterling was one of the most important factors in their decision.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Among Yes voters, the biggest single motivation was "disaffection with Westminster politics".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Cameron admitted he was "very embarrassed" for revealing the Queen's political view, which she had guarded in her own comments.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Alex Salmond, the Scottish First Minister and leader of the SNP, stated that he accepted the "verdict of the people" and called upon "all Scots to follow suit in accepting the democratic verdict of the people of Scotland".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] He called the referendum a "triumph for the democratic process and for participation in politics".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] He also resigned as SNP leader and as First Minister, saying that "for me as leader my time is nearly over but for Scotland the campaign continues and the dream shall never die".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Northern Ireland's First Minister Peter Robinson and Welsh First Minister Carwyn Jones responded positively to the result.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Robinson was "delighted Scotland has voted to remain in the Union".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] There was a large international reaction to the results of the Scottish independence referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The White House congratulated Scotland on their "full and energetic exercise of democracy".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] President Barack Obama noted the "debate, discussion, and passionate yet peaceful deliberations" and welcomed the result, saying he looked forward to "continuing our strong and special relationship with all the people of Great Britain and Northern Ireland".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] John Baird, the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Canada, welcomed the decision and praised the conduct of the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Angela Merkel, the Chancellor of Germany, said that, "We [the German government] have always respected the fact that this referendum was called and that the central government in London agreed to this.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] And now we respect the outcome of it as well".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] When asked how she felt about the result she replied "I will not comment on this but just smile".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] We look forward to working with all parties across these islands in the years ahead.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Good Friday Agreement of 1998 is the historic template for harmonious and mutually beneficial development of the totality of relationships among the peoples of these islands.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In particular, it has led to a transformation in relationships between the two great traditions on this island".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] We have noted that the UK government has extended concrete promises in this regard.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Facing the result of the referendum, Erna Solberg, Prime Minister of Norway, stated to Norwegian broadcaster NRK she was 'glad' Scotland chose to remain in the union and that Scottish independence could have become challenging for Norway as a neighboring country.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Spanish Prime Minister Mariano Rajoy, in a video message, said that the Scottish have avoided serious consequences and "have chosen the most favorable option for everyone; for themselves, for all of Britain, and for the rest of Europe".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Iñigo Urkullu, the President of the Basque Country, stated on the day of the referendum that as the British Government had allowed Scotland to freely decide its own future, the responsibility of the Basque government was to "follow Scotland's footsteps" in securing a similar agreement in Spain.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Artur Mas, President of the Generalitat of Catalonia, described the referendum as a model for a future vote in the Catalonia, and said "What happened in Scotland is not a setback for us, because what we really want in Catalonia is to have the chance to vote".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the day after the Scottish referendum, the Catalan parliament voted to hold a "popular consultation" on Catalan independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Spanish government said that such a vote would be unconstitutional, but a referendum was held on 9 November 2014 anyway.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The large majority (80%) voted for Catalonia to be an independent country, although two-thirds of Catalans did not participate in the referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Secretary General of NATO Anders Fogh Rasmussen said that he fully-respected "the choice that the people of Scotland have made".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] President of the European Commission José Manuel Barroso said the Scottish vote was good for a "united, open, and stronger Europe".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Ten voters discovered that someone had voted under their names at polling stations in Glasgow, a method of fraud termed 'personation', and this led to an investigation by Police Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] During a BBC results broadcast, Scottish Conservative Party leader Ruth Davidson said that "No" campaigners had been "taking tallies" of postal votes and that those showed that the "No" campaign was in the lead.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This resulted in complaints to the electoral commission because the Scottish Independence Referendum Act 2013 stated that people attending proceedings related to the receipt of postal votes must not attempt to ascertain the outcome or "communicate any information" from that voting.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The Electoral Commission, who could not investigate criminal allegations, passed the complaints onto Police Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A formal investigation was subsequently opened, which concluded that there was no criminality.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] According to official Russian observers, the conditions under which the votes were counted were not up to international standards and that the procedure used made it impossible to check on irregularities.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Russia's criticism came just months after the international community had rejected the results of a Kremlin-backed referendum held in the Russian-occupied Ukrainian territory of Crimea.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Russian officials said that the strong performance of the Scottish National Party (SNP) at the 2015 general election confirmed their suspicions about the Scottish independence referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A petition demanding a second referendum, based on allegations of vote-miscounting, gained more than 70,000 signatures within 24 hours.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In response, Chief Counting Officer Mary Pitcaithly declared that the referendum had been "properly conducted".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An official spokesperson reiterated this point, saying that they were "satisfied that all counts throughout Scotland were properly conducted" and that incidents in the footage could be "easily explained" and were being presented as a "'conspiracy' theory".
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] On the night of 19 September, hundreds of unionists arrived to celebrate the 'No'-vote and some attacked independence supporters who had gathered in George Square, Glasgow.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Many of the unionists waved Union Jacks or loyalist flags and chanted "Rule, Britannia!" Police officers were drafted in to separate the groups but some unionists broke through police lines.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A number of people were reportedly beaten and bottles were thrown.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A press-photographer told *The Scotsman* he saw people being "kicked about" and was forced to flee after being threatened.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] By the end of the following month, the police had made 32 arrests in relation to the events.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The violence was condemned by politicians from both the 'Yes'- and 'No'-camps.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the weeks following the referendum, thousands of people joined the Scottish National Party, the Scottish Greens, or the Scottish Socialist Party, which had all campaigned for a 'Yes'-vote.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The parties claimed that many of the new members were former Scottish Labour Party members.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] By 2 October 2014, SNP membership had tripled from 25,000 to 75,000 people, overtaking the Liberal Democrats as the third-largest political party in the UK.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Conservative MP David Mundell said that 80,000 people had signed up to their "Friends of the Union" group during the campaign.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] These people had not necessarily become full members of the Conservative Party because they were not focussed on increasing the number of "card-carrying" members.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Following the referendum, there were calls for greater unity within Scottish unionism and to vote tactically against nationalist candidates.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] A grassroots campaign called "Scotland in Union" aimed to encourage tactical voting at the 2015 general election and to publicise the benefits of Scotland being a part of the United Kingdom.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Analysis by the Electoral Reform Society prior to the 2015 general election identified some constituencies where tactical voting could succeed, but also pointed out that many voters would find it difficult to support another political party.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Writing after the election, Professor John Curtice said that in only one constituency (Edinburgh South) could it be said that tactical voting succeeded in defeating an SNP candidate.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Two days before the referendum, the leaders of the three main UK political parties publicly pledged to devolve "extensive new powers" to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] They also agreed to a timetable proposed by Gordon Brown.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In his speech responding to the referendum results, David Cameron said that an all-party commission, chaired by Lord Smith of Kelvin, would oversee the implementation of the new powers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Cameron also called for an answer to the West Lothian question, by removing the right of Scottish MPs to vote on legislation relating only to England.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This proposal was opposed by Gordon Brown, who signed a petition calling for the additional powers to be devolved without any other conditions being attached.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The proposals were debated at length by the UK and Scottish parliaments.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The bill devolving further powers to Scotland was approved unanimously by the Scottish Parliament in March 2016.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Following the referendum, the SNP took a clear lead over the other parties in Scottish opinion polls.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the 2015 general election, the SNP received 1,454,436 votes, 49.97% of the Scottish vote and 56 out of the 59 Scottish seats contested in the election.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Labour lost forty of their forty-one seats and the Liberal Democrats lost ten of their eleven seats – all to the SNP.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] The SNP replaced the Liberal Democrats as the third largest party in the House of Commons.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] As the Conservatives won an overall majority in the 2015 UK general election, a UK-wide referendum on European Union membership was held in June 2016.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] An overall majority of the UK voted to leave the EU (for "Brexit"), while all of Scotland's council areas voted to remain in the EU.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Shortly afterwards, First Minister Nicola Sturgeon announced her intention to prepare legislation for a second independence referendum.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] In the June 2017 general election, the first major electoral test after the EU referendum, the SNP won 35 of the 59 Scottish seats in the House of Commons.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] This represented a drop of 21 seats from 2015, with the Conservatives, Labour and Liberal Democrats all making gains.
[src:bank-of-scotland/2014-scottish-independence-referendum-p04] Those results were largely reversed in the December 2019 general election, as the SNP won 48 seats and the Conservatives and Labour both made net losses.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] It was created in September in 2011 following the "bankisation" of Novacaixagalicia savings bank as NCG Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] It operates in the autonomous communities of Galicia, Asturias and the province of León, in other parts of Spain and in Portugal, as well as offices in the United Kingdom, Germany, France, Switzerland, Brazil, Venezuela, Panama, Mexico and the United States, places with strong Galician communities.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Abanca has been designated as a significant institution since the entry into force of European Banking Supervision in late 2014, and as a consequence is directly supervised by the European Central Bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The bank was founded as *NCG Banco, S.A.* in September 2011 following the bankisation process of Novacaixagalicia.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The company would operate as *Novagalicia Banco* in Galicia, Asturias and León and as *EVO Banco* in the rest of Spain.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Abanca originated from the savings bank NovaCaixaGalicia, established on December 1, 2010, following the merger of Caixa Galicia and Caixanova.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This formation was a response to the stipulations of Royal Decree Law 2/2011, which necessitated the creation of a banking entity to manage the operations previously handled by NovaCaixaGalicia.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] At its inception, this subsidiary was wholly owned by the savings bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On September 14, 2011, NCG Banco, S.A. was established, with José María Castellano appointed as the executive chairman and César González-Bueno Mayer as the CEO.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Notably, NCG Banco was the first bank to incorporate the Galician language in its founding deed.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On September 30, 2011, the European Commission in Brussels authorized the nationalization of NCG Banco, along with Catalunya Banc and Unnim Banc.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] As Novagalicia Banco's predecessor, the savings bank Novacaixagalicia, was subsequently bailed out by the Government of Spain the majority of the shares in the company were held by the bailout program Fund for Orderly Bank Restructuring (90.57%).
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] As part of this process, NCG Banco received €2,465 million in capital from the Fund for Orderly Bank Restructuring (FROB).
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Consequently, the FROB acquired a 93.16% stake in NCG Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The Novacaixagalicia Foundation holds 6.84% with the remaining 2.59% being held by private investors.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Consequently, without its banking business, NovaCaixaGalicia's role was reduced to financially supporting its social work through the revenues derived from its ownership stake in NCG Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On October 19, 2011, the commercial brand Novagalicia Banco was launched.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Subsequently, on November 14, it was announced that the bank would operate under two distinct brands and business models: Novagalicia Banco serving Galicia, Asturias, Castilla y León, and international markets, and NGB covering the rest of Spain.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This strategic adjustment also led to the formation of two new business units: one dedicated to wholesale banking and the other, known as the Singular Asset Management Unit (UGAS), focusing on non-strategic assets.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On January 12, 2012, 17 Galician businessmen entered the bank's capital through the purchase of 2.59% of the capital from the Fund for Orderly Bank Restructuring (FROB).
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This was divided between 90.57% of the FROB, 2.59% of the private investors and 6.84% of NovaCaixaGalicia.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On 12 March 2012 NCG Banco, S.A. began operating its assets outside of Galicia under the brand name *EVO Banco* and launched its main financial product the Cuenta Inteligente.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] In its first four weeks EVO Banco had attracted 8,290 clients and 70 million euros worth of investment.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On March 22, NCG Banco, S.A. and its union representatives came to an agreement to avoid forced layoff.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On July 12, 2012, the bank launched a media campaign featuring personal apologies from its Executive Chairman and CEO to its customers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This campaign addressed the previous investments in real estate made by the two savings banks that merged to form the bank during Spain's real estate bubble.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Additionally, it acknowledged the sale of preferred shares to customers who were unaware of the associated risks.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This initiative marked the first instance of a Spanish bank undertaking such a public apology campaign.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On December 27, 2012, FROB injected €5,425 million of aid from the European Stability Mechanism (ESM) into the bank, assuming full control of the entity.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] As a result, NovaCaixaGalicia transitioned into a special character foundation due to the loss of its capital in NCG Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Concurrently, the FROB converted €1,162 million worth of preferred shares, initially subscribed in December 2010 by NovaCaixaGalicia, into ordinary shares.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] As part of NCG Banco's restructuring plan, it was determined that by 2017 the bank should concentrate its business model on retail lending and lending to small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) within its primary historical regions.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The plan also included discontinuing credit lines associated with real estate developments and reducing its activities in the wholesale market.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On July 19, 2013, the Deposit Guarantee Fund (FGD) acquired a 25.57% stake in NCG Banco following a disbursement of €801.7 million, aimed at providing liquidity to the bank's preference shareholders and subordinated debt holders.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] After this transaction, the remaining ownership was distributed as follows: the FROB held 63%; hybrid instrument holders owned 9% (with 2% held by retail investors and 7% by wholesale investors); and the bank itself retained 2% as treasury stock.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On 9 September 2013 Novagalicia Banco announced that it would sell the EVO Banco division to the American private equity firm Apollo Global Management for 60 million euros.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On October 18, 2013, EVO Banco was registered in the Special Registry of Banks and Bankers of the Bank of Spain.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On November 19, 2013, FROB initiated the binding bidding process for the sale of NCG Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Potential bidders included notable banking institutions such as Banco Santander, BBVA, CaixaBank, and the Venezuelan bank Banesco, alongside investment funds like Guggenheim, WL Ross, J.C.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The deadline for submitting binding bids was set for December 16.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Following the review of these bids, provided no single offer was overwhelmingly more favorable, a second phase would commence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This phase would involve selecting the three entities with the best proposals, who would then be invited to submit their final offers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On December 9, 2013, NCG Banco finalized the transfer of assets, liabilities, customers, employees, and services to EVO Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This completion occurred three months after the signing of the pre-sale agreement with Apollo European Principal Finance Fund II (Apollo EPF II), a fund managed by entities affiliated with Apollo Global Management.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On December 18, 2013, Banco Etcheverría, a subsidiary of Banesco, emerged as the winner in the first phase of the auction for NCG Banco with a bid of €1,003 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This bid did not include public aid but incorporated additional guarantees of €275 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] As a result, Banco Etcheverría acquired an 88.33% stake in NCG Banco, which was primarily held by the FROB and the Deposit Guarantee Fund (FGD).
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The FROB received €712 million for its shares, culminating in a total loss to taxpayers of €8,269 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Meanwhile, the FGD obtained €291 million from the sale, leaving a deficit of €511 million in the financial system.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On February 28, 2014, NCG Banco completed the transfer of all shares of EVO Banco to the Apollo fund, finalizing the acquisition of EVO Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Following the conclusion of this sale, NCG Banco expanded its presence by opening branches in other Spanish cities under the Novagalicia Banco brand.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Subsequently, Novagalicia Banco began opening branches in other cities in Spain under its own brand.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On 11 November 2013, the Spanish government bailout program Fund for Orderly Bank Restructuring (FROB) began the privatization process of Novagalicia Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] In April 2014, Banesco announced that the Novagalicia Banco brand would be discontinued following the completion of its acquisition of NCG Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On June 20, 2014, the European Commission approved the sale of NCG Banco along with the proposed amendments to its restructuring plan.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The sale was finalised on 25 June 2014 when Banesco, Banco Etcheverría's parent company, made an initial payment of €403 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Banesco would pay a further €200 million on 30 June 2017 and the final payment of €300 million a year later.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The board of directors was constituted, which approved the appointment of Banco Etcheverría's chairman, Javier Etcheverría, as chairman of NCG Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The acquisition was conducted through Banesco Holding Financiero 2, S.L.U., which held the majority of the capital of Banco Etcheverría.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Following the acquisition, Banesco Holding Financiero changed its corporate name to Abanca Holding Financiero, S.L.U.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On June 27, 2014, the bank commenced operations under the Abanca brand name, replacing the previously used Novagalicia Banco brand.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The following day, at an event held in the Galician capital, Santiago de Compostela, Novagalicia Banco revealed the new brand name for their bank: ABANCA (from **a banca**; Galician for "the bank"), a change which went into effect the very same day in all branches throughout the region.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On October 6, 2014, the General Shareholders' Meetings of NCG Banco and Banco Etcheverría approved the merger by absorption of Banco Etcheverría by NCG Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The merger was finalized on November 14, 2014, with the resulting entity establishing its headquarters in Betanzos.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] In December 2014 the company announced the merger of NCG Banco, S.A. with parent company Banco Echeverria, S.A.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The company changed its legal name to ABANCA Corporación Bancaria, S.A. and its headquarters would be in the town of Betanzos, in the former headquarters of Banco Echeverria.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On May 2, 2017, Abanca announced an agreement to acquire 100% of Popular Servicios Financieros, previously the consumer finance division of Banco Pastor, for €39 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The transaction was completed in September of the same year, initiating the integration process of Abanca Consumer Finance and Popular Servicios Financieros, which was subsequently renamed Abanca Servicios Financieros.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On 27 March 2018 Deutsche Bank announced its private and commercial client business in Portugal would be acquired by Abanca for €6.5bn.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The business resumed trading Start of business on 11 June 2019.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On May 4, 2018, Eduardo Eraña Guerra assumed the interim chairmanship of the entity while Juan Carlos Escotet, the principal owner, attended to the affairs of Banesco in Venezuela, which was undergoing intervention by the Venezuelan government.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On November 22, 2018, the Portuguese Council of Ministers announced that Abanca had been selected as the successful bidder for Banco Caixa Geral, the Spanish subsidiary of the Portuguese bank Caixa Geral de Depósitos, with the acquisition valued at approximately €364 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On February 22, 2019, Abanca announced a conditional takeover bid of €1.7 billion for Liberbank, stipulating that it be granted access to the bank's accounts before March 1.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] However, the bid was withdrawn after the National Securities Market Commission (CNMV) prohibited the conditional nature of the offer and due to insufficient support from Liberbank's shareholders.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On April 29, 2019, the Boards of Directors of Abanca Corporación Bancaria, S.A.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] (the absorbing entity) and Abanca Holding Financiero, S.A.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] (the absorbed entity) approved the Common Merger Plan for the two companies.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On June 8 and 9, 2019, the integration of Deutsche Bank PCB Portugal into Abanca was successfully completed.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On June 10, 2019, the merger between Abanca Corporación Bancaria and Abanca Holding Financiero was approved at the Ordinary General Shareholders' Meeting of Abanca Corporación Bancaria, S.A.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On October 14, 2019, Abanca completed the acquisition of Banco Caixa Geral for a total of €384 million, an increase from the initially estimated €364 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This acquisition brought Abanca's control over Banco Caixa Geral's capital to 99.79%.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Following the merger, Abanca gained an additional €7 billion in business from over 131,000 customers, as well as 110 new branches and more than 500 employees, particularly enhancing its presence in the provinces near the Portuguese border.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On February 27, 2020, the reverse merger between Abanca Corporación Bancaria (the absorbing company) and Abanca Holding Financiero (the absorbed company) was officially registered in the Mercantile Registry of La Coruña.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On March 16, 2020, Abanca completed the technological, brand, and legal integration of Banco Caixa Geral.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This followed the legal and accounting merger of the two entities, which was finalized on March 13 with its registration in the Commercial Registry of La Coruña.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On January 28, 2021, Abanca finalized the acquisition of Bankoa from Crédit Agricole.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This transaction enabled the Galician entity to increase its business volume by €4,267 million to €93,850 million, expand its commercial network with 30 branches and 3 corporate agencies primarily located in the Basque Country, and gain over 40,000 new customers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The acquisition involved the formal purchase of 99.81% of Bankoa's capital for €122.4 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] For the remaining approximately 0.2% of shares, Abanca offered 18.3 of its own shares for each share of Bankoa.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On April 26, 2021, the board of directors of Abanca approved the merger with Bankoa.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On November 12, 2021, the merger between Abanca and Bankoa was officially registered with the Mercantile Registry.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On November 14, 2021, Abanca completed the integration of Bankoa, finalizing the process with two key operations: the implementation of the brand and the transfer of activity to Abanca's technological and operational platforms.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Following these steps, Abanca began operations in the Basque Country, Navarre, and La Rioja under the Bankoa Abanca brand.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On April 5, 2021, Abanca announced an agreement to acquire the Spanish business of Novo Banco.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This acquisition was projected to elevate Abanca's business volume to 100,000 million euros, enhancing its presence in personal and private banking as well as corporate business sectors.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] With this operation, Abanca would manage assets totaling 71,338 million euros, loans and advances to customers amounting to 42,368 million euros, deposits of 46,037 million euros, and off-balance sheet liabilities of 11,789 million euros.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The entity would also comprise 6,312 employees and 745 branches.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Remarkably, Abanca agreed to pay one euro for this transaction.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The purchase was finalized on November 30, 2021, and the transition to the Abanca branding began, with technological integration anticipated to occur in the last quarter of 2022.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] In February 2022, aiming to improve banking accessibility for the elderly, Abanca announced a series of initiatives across its branches.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] These measures included offering individualized attention to elderly customers through personal managers, extending branch opening hours to 14:00, and a strong commitment to maintaining operations in the 134 municipalities where it is the sole financial institution.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] On December 22, 2022, Abanca announced the initiation of exclusive negotiations with Banque Fédérative du Crédit Mutuel (BFCM) for the acquisition of TARGOBANK España.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The sale and purchase agreement were officially signed by both parties on February 22, 2023.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] The transaction was successfully concluded on October 6, 2023, marking the start of the technological integration process, which is scheduled to be completed in 2024.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] This acquisition resulted in a 6 billion euro increase in turnover, approximately 5.6% more than Abanca's total prior to the transaction.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Moreover, the acquisition expanded Abanca's geographical footprint into the Mediterranean arc, Madrid, and Andalusia.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Abanca has two operating headquarters; the institutional and business address in Vigo, and the social and tax address in A Coruña.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] As of September 30, 2023, Abanca maintained a network of 677 branches and employed 6,288 individuals.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Within Spain, the bank operated 623 branches.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] In the Basque Country, Navarra, and La Rioja, it conducted business under the Bankoa Abanca brand.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abanca] Abanca also had a presence in Portugal with 70 points of sale and extended its operations to nine additional countries across Europe and America.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The **Abbey National Building Society** was formed in 1944 by the merger of the Abbey Road and the National building societies.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] It was the first building society in the United Kingdom to demutualise, doing so in July 1989.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The bank expanded through a number of acquisitions in the 1990s, including James Hay, Scottish Mutual, Scottish Provident and the rail leasing company Porterbrook.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Abbey National launched an online bank, Cahoot, in June 2000.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In September 2003, the bank rebranded as Abbey, and in November 2004, it became a wholly owned subsidiary of the Spanish Santander Group, with a rebrand following in February 2005.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In January 2010, the savings business of Bradford & Bingley was combined with the bank, and Abbey National plc was renamed Santander UK plc.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Prior to the takeover, Abbey National plc was a constituent of the FTSE 100 Index.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The National Building Society had its origins in the freehold land movement, sometimes called the “forty shilling freeholders movement”.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In country areas, the voting entitlement was dependent on the possession of freehold land with an annual value of £2.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] This required a capital outlay of some £60-70 and was outside the reach of the average worker.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] A scheme to obviate this capital requirement was launched in 1847 as the Birmingham Freehold Land Society.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In simple terms, the society arranged for the purchase of tracts of land and divided them into plots which individuals could purchase, the cost being met by regular subscriptions.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The success of the Birmingham Society prompted a flood of other societies around the country, of which the National was one.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In 1849 The Metropolitan Freehold Land Society was formed, led by such prominent MPs as Joshua Walmsley, Joseph Hume and above all Richard Cobden.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] An application was made to register under the 1836 Building Societies Act but the registrar refused to accept the name.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Accordingly, the name was changed to The National Permanent Mutual Building Society, with an authorization for it to be commonly called The National Freehold Land Society.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Despite the building society registration and formal name, there was no doubt as to the National's function.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The 1852 Prospectus clearly stated that “The special objects of this Society are to facilitate the acquisition of freehold land, and the erection of houses thereon – to enable such of its members as are eligible, to obtain the county franchise”.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] (The name was changed in 1894 to The National Freehold Land and Building Society and finally to The National Building Society in 1930).
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The Society was not allowed to purchase land in its own name, so purchases were made by the Trustees and quickly thirteen estates were purchased around London.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Within four years, the National had become the largest land society in the country.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] There were over 100 such societies in existence and the National claimed to be taking forty per cent of the funds.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Once the plots had been purchased, the National recognized the need to provide finance for the houses that were to be built on them.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In 1854 it published its first advert, inviting applications for advances “for the erection of houses on the Estates”; those advances were not to exceed two-thirds of the net value and to be repaid over ten years.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Because the Society was not legally allowed to hold land in its own name, in 1858 it formed a separate company British Land to take over all the land previously held in the name of the Trustees.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] All the capital was subscribed by the National's own investors but although British Land was financially distinct, there was a commonality of directors and staff.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The objective was to make the National “more emphatically than it has ever been yet, a Savings Bank and Building Society.” At that point, British Land accounted for two thirds of the National's advances.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The importance of British Land to the National gradually diminished although it was not until 1874 that the proportion fell to below one half; after an internal row over the ownership of the National's head office, all the advances were repaid in 1878.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The repayment of the British Land loans marked the final break with the old freehold land movement and this was formalized in 1880 when the National incorporated under the Building Societies Act 1874.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] This gave it two important advantages: it could act under its own name and it afforded limited liability to its members, probably a comfort after the events of 1878.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In that year the City of Glasgow Bank collapsed creating widespread financial uncertainty.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In the event, funds flowed into the National in excess of its ability to find borrowers and it decided to deploy surplus funds in the north of England.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Losses were incurred and the National confined its operations to within 100 miles of London.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Elkington described the 30 years from 1890 as a period of consolidation with the Society always in the top dozen nationally.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] However, in the period after WW1 there was exceptional growth both for the industry and the National in particular.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Over a 15-year period the advances of the Building Societies Association rose eight-fold whereas those of the National rose by a factor of twenty.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The Abbey was founded in 1874 by members of the Free Church in Abbey Road and of the Abbey Road Church Benefit Society.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The chosen name of the society was the Abbey Road and St John's Wood Mutual Benefit Building Society and it was launched in 1875.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Three years later the Society registered under the Building Societies Act 1874 (37 & 38 Vict. c.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] 42) and the name was changed to the Abbey Road and St John's Wood Permanent Building Society.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In contrast to the high-profile public figures who founded the National, the start of Abbey Road was more modest.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] By 1888, the address was still at the schoolroom of the Abbey Road Church and the Secretary advised that he would be available on Friday evenings at his home.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The early years saw rapid growth in members of the Society from 111 in that first year to over 1,000 in 1884, reaching 2,000 in 1881, 3,000 in 1901 and over 7,000 by the outbreak of WWI.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] A new office was eventually required in 1906.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] However, even after the War, the Abbey Road “was little known outside the borough of Paddington in which it was situated” The catalyst for change was the arrival of Sir Harold Bellman, later a commanding figure in the building society sector.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] He joined the board of management in 1918 and became Secretary of the Society in 1921.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] He overhauled every aspect of the operations, introduced improvements, advertised in the national press and opened branches outside the Society's home area.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] By 1929, the number of members had exceeded 100,000 and these doubled in the following two years.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] It was in this inter-war period that Abbey overtook the National in size: in 1918, the National had £1.2m assets against Abbey Road's £0.8m whereas in 1939 Abbey's assets totalled £51m against the £36m of the National.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In 1932, the society moved into new headquarters, Abbey House, at 219–229 Baker Street, London, which it occupied until 2002.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The site was thought to include 221B Baker Street, the fictional home of Sherlock Holmes, and for many years Abbey employed a secretary charged with answering mail sent to Holmes at that address.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] WWII brought a cessation to new housebuilding and the building societies preoccupation was supporting mortgage owners and the consequences of bomb damage to properties.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] By 1943, as the prospect of victory increased, the Government led discussions on post-war reconstruction.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The National's Chairman, Stanley Ramsey, argued that greater scale would be needed to deal with the financial challenges of reconstruction and in 1943 he proposed a merger to the Abbey Road.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The merger under the **Abbey National Building Society** name was implemented at the beginning of 1944 with Sir Harold Bellman as chairman and Stanley Ramsey as his deputy.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] At the time of the merger, Abbey Road was the second largest society and National, the sixth.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The post-war Labour government ensured that resources for housing reconstruction was almost entirely concentrated on local authority housing, while stringent controls severely limited the private sector, the building societies’ natural market.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Between 1951 and 1954, the Conservative government removed building controls and the growth in home ownership and private housebuilding resumed.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] However, the Society still had little more than a hundred branches and, with the pre-war management still in control, perhaps it was no longer as innovative.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Eventually, 1963 saw the departure of the “old guard”: Chairman Harold Bellman died aged 76; Bruce Wycherley, general manager of the National from 1933 and chief executive of the merged group from 1948, resigned, as did Stanley Ramsey the “original architect” of the merger.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Abbey National was now set for rapid expansion.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] By 1968, the branch network had reached 150 and assets exceeded £1bn.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In the next ten years the business of four other societies was acquired: the Definite Permanent in 1968, The State Building Society in 1970, Highgate Building Society in 1974 and the Oak Co-operative in 1979.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In 1971, the Abbey was opening a branch per week and in 1974, the peak of the private housing boom, there were 335 branches and £3bn. assets.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] This growth could not have taken place without the increase in new private housebuilding and the expansion in home ownership that created the second-hand market; it also reflected more innovative marketing policies.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] This innovation reached its peak with the appointment of Clive Thornton as general manager in 1979.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] He led a wide range of marketing initiatives, perhaps the best known being the registration of the name "Granny Bonds" to rival the National Savings product.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Thornton was more than a passive supplier of funds to house purchasers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] He took an activist approach to the housebuilding industry arguing that building societies should finance building of houses and flats to rent privately.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In 1980, the Abbey set aside £250m to stimulate the private homes sector.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Thornton worked with Local Authorities to finance inner city renovation, one of the best-known examples being the loan of £3m to the Stockbridge Village Trust to help regenerate 4,000 houses on a rundown council estate in Knowsley.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Abbey even formed its own private housebuilding company, Abbey National Homes, in 1986.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] It built 2-300 houses a year but during the housing recession of 1990-92 it lost over £50m and was closed.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The range of services offered brought Abbey National ever closer to a clearing bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In 1988, Abbey introduced a full-service interest-bearing cheque account; its administration was restricted by building society rules and the need to find a partner that could clear Abbey's cheques (The Co-operative Bank).
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Later, Abbey became a full member of the Bankers' Automated Clearing Services (BACS) and became member of the BACS and CHAPS clearing systems.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The stage was set for Abbey to end its mutual status and become a public company.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The Abbey National Building Society became the first of the United Kingdom building societies to demutualise, and became a public limited company as Abbey National plc on 12 July 1989.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Members of the society were given 100 free shares, and had the option to purchase further shares at £1.30, while the opening price per share on the LSE was £1.61.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] After demutualisation, small investors owned a third of the company.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The demutualisation process was marred by the discovery of a large number of undelivered share certificates awaiting destruction at a contractor's premises.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Abbey National shares peaked at more than £14 in 2000, before the stock market began a long decline.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] After losses of at least £243 million, Abbey National decided to sell its estate agency business Cornerstone to two entrepreneurs, Tony Snarey and Bill McClintock, in a management buyout backed by insurance company Provident Life for £8 million in August 1993.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The 347-strong chain employed 1,800 staff and was subject to a write-down of £138 million in March 1993 following annual losses since 1989 of at c. £20 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Having sold off around 280 branches in 1994, the remaining 70 branches of Cornerstone (although over 200 of the sold branches continued to use the name at the time) were put into receivership in October 1995.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In July 1994, Abbey National purchased James Hay, one of the United Kingdom's foremost independent providers of self administered pensions.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] James Hay then went on to grow in strength and launched Abbey Wrap, a service in which IFAs can keep the clients' ISAs, PEPs, offshore bonds, and SIPP in one place.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Abbey Wrap Managers was FSA approved in August 2003.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] This was relaunched as James Hay Wrap in June 2005.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In February 1995, Abbey National Baring Derivatives were taken down along with Barings Bank, due to failures in regulation and control, especially in regards to Nick Leeson of Barings Bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In the summer of 1995, Abbey National purchased First National Finance Corporation, a consumer credit company, for about £285 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Two life assurance companies were demutualised and acquired, Scottish Mutual Assurance in 1992 and Scottish Provident in 2001, which enabled Abbey to pursue the bancassurance model.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In August 1996, Abbey National took over the National & Provincial Building Society, which was itself the product of a 1982 merger between the Provincial Building Society and the Burnley Building Society.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] This merger increased Abbey National's branch network by almost two hundred branches and brought in three million more customers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In April 2000, Abbey bought Porterbrook from Stagecoach Group for £773 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Porterbrook was one of the three railway rolling stock operating companies created from by the privatisation of British Rail, leasing rolling stock to the train operating companies in the United Kingdom.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The bank launched its online bank, Cahoot, in June 2000.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In August 2000 The First National subsidiary purchased Highway Vehicle Management from GUS plc for £170 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Lloyds TSB attempted to merge with the bank in July 2001, though that was ultimately rejected by the Competition Commission.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] At first, this provided a good profit stream, despite the criticisms of some analysts.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] This eventually undid the company, however, when Enron turned out to be unsafe and the 11 September attacks in New York damaged confidence in various financial areas.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] From this point, Abbey struggled from financial losses and a tarnished image.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The chief executive, Ian Harley, a long-time Abbey employee, resigned and his post was filled by an outsider, Luqman Arnold.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Arnold spearheaded a major reorganisation of the bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The First National business was sold, with the car hire business sold to Lloyds TSB for £46 million, with the remaining business sold to General Electric for £848 million.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In September 2003 the brand name was shortened to Abbey, the abbey.com domain name launched and the Abbey National umbrella logo dropped.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Banking literature was also simplified as part of the programme, labelled 'turning banking on its head'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] On 26 July 2004, Abbey National plc and Banco Santander Central Hispano, SA announced that they had reached agreement on the terms of a recommended acquisition by Banco Santander of Abbey.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Following shareholders' approval at the EGMs of Abbey (95 per cent voted in favour, despite vocal opposition from most of those present) and Santander, the acquisition was formally approved by the courts and Abbey became part of the Santander Group on 12 November 2004.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Francisco Gómez Roldán took over as chief executive from Luqman Arnold, who received a rumoured £5 million, made up of pay off and share options.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Gómez-Roldán died suddenly in July 2006, three weeks before being succeeded by Antonio Horta Osorio.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In June 2006, Abbey agreed to sell its life businesses to Resolution plc.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The businesses sold to Resolution were Scottish Mutual Assurance, Scottish Provident Limited and Abbey National Life, two offshore life companies, Scottish Mutual International and Scottish Provident International Life Assurance Limited.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] In July 2007, Abbey admitted that errors that it made in the 1980s have contributed to many borrowers' mortgage terms being extended by up to 15 years.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] During this period – which saw considerable turbulence in interest rates – Abbey extended the terms on customers' repayment style mortgages without their knowledge.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The Financial Ombudsman Service stated that Abbey customers may be eligible for compensation.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] As a result of the banking crisis of 2008, Abbey purchased the savings business and branches of Bradford & Bingley in September 2008 following the nationalisation of B&B by HM Government.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The purchase of Alliance & Leicester by Santander had been agreed earlier that month.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Abbey migrated all customer accounts to the Partenon computer software used by Santander in June 2008.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] On 27 October 2008, Abbey reached an agreement to sell Porterbrook to a consortium of Deutsche Bank, Lloyds TSB and Antin Infrastructure Partners.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The Santander Group announced in May 2009 that Abbey and the Bradford & Bingley branch network would be renamed under the Santander brand on 11 January 2010.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Credit cards issued by Abbey were the first to change to Santander.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] The Cater Allen, James Hay and Cahoot brands remained.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Santander UK plc also retained the name Abbey National Treasury Services ltd ("ANTS") for the division responsible for managing its liquidity, risk management and wholesale banking needs.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Abbey's registered office was in London (built on the site of the former Thames Television studios in Euston Road) and its main corporate centre was in Milton Keynes.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Its savings and banking administration departments were in Bradford, with mortgage centres in Thornaby-on-Tees and Whiteley (which closed in 2010).
[src:bank-of-scotland/abbey-national] Investments were previously branded as Inscape, but were renamed Premium Investments in the end of 2008, provided by Santander Portfolio Management.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Following aggressive international expansion, ABN AMRO was acquired and broken up in 2007–2008 by a consortium of European banks, including Fortis which intended to take over its formed operations in the Benelux region.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Fortis came under stress in the autumn of 2008, and was in turn broken up into separate national entities; the Dutch operations, namely Fortis Bank Nederland and the former ABN AMRO activities that Fortis had planned to absorb, were nationalized, restructured, and renamed ABN AMRO in mid-2010.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 20 November 2015, the Dutch government publicly re-listed the company through an IPO and sold 20 percent of the shares to the public.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] ABN AMRO has been designated as a Significant Institution since the entry into force of European Banking Supervision in late 2014, and as a consequence is directly supervised by the European Central Bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In 1824, King William I established the Nederlandsche Handel-Maatschappij (NHM) a trading company to revive trade and financing of the Dutch East Indies and it would become one of the primary ancestors of ABN AMRO.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The NHM merged with the *Twentsche Bank* in 1964, to form Algemene Bank Nederland (ABN).
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Also in 1964, the *Amsterdamsche Bank*, established in 1871, merged with the *Rotterdamsche Bank*, established in 1873 (as part of a merger that included *Determeijer Weslingh & Zn.* from 1765), to form Amsterdamsche en Rotterdamsche Bank, known as AMRO Bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 22 September 1991, ABN and AMRO merged to form ABN AMRO.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In 1993, two of its investment banking subsidiaries ― Bank Mees & Hope and Pierson, Heldring & Pierson ― merged in turn to form MeesPierson.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The two merged banks brought to ABN AMRO a large network of overseas companies and branches.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] From NHM, ABN owned a significant branch network in Asia and the Middle East, including the Saudi Hollandi Bank owned by the NHM Jeddah branch.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Another, the Hollandsche Bank-Unie (HBU), which grew from the merger of the *Hollandsche Bank voor de Middellandsche Zee* (HBMZ) and the *Hollandsche Zuid-Amerika Bank* in 1933, gave ABN AMRO an extensive network of branches in South and Central America.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In 1979, ABN had expanded into North America with the acquisition of Chicago-based LaSalle National Bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In 2005, Standard Federal became *LaSalle Bank Midwest* to unite ABN AMRO's two banking networks in the U.S.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In 1995, ABN AMRO purchased The Chicago Corporation, an American securities and commodities trading and clearing corporation.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Other major acquisitions included the Brazilian bank Banco Real in 1998, and the Italian bank Antonveneta in 2006.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] It was also involved in the controversial acquisition of the Dutch local government mortgage and building development organisation, the Bouwfonds in 2000.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] ABN AMRO sold the Bouwfonds as a going concern in 2006.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In July 2006, Favonius Ventures, which was founded and headed by Roel Pieper, received all of the technology investments of ABN AMRO Capital which is the private equity business unit of ABN AMRO Bank N.V.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] ABN AMRO had come to a crossroads in early 2005.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The bank had still not come close to its own target of having a return on equity that would put it among the top five of its peer group, a target that the CEO, Rijkman Groenink had set upon his appointment in 2000.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] From 2000 until 2005, ABN AMRO's stock price stagnated.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Financial results in 2006 added to concerns about the bank's future.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Operating expenses increased at a greater rate than operating revenue, and the efficiency ratio deteriorated further to 69.9%.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Non-performing loans increased considerably year on year by 192%.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Net profits were only boosted by sustained asset sales.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In 2006, research findings were publicly released regarding ABN AMRO Bank N.V.'s predecessors and connections to African slavery.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] An examination of 200 predecessors of ABN AMRO Bank N.V. founded before 1888 determined that some had connections to African slavery, either in the United States or elsewhere in the Americas.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] By 2007, ABN AMRO was the second-largest bank in the Netherlands and the eighth-largest in Europe by assets.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] At that time, the magazine *The Banker* and Fortune Global 500 placed it 15th in the list of world's biggest banks and it had operations in 63 countries, with over 110,000 employees.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Pakistan merged with Prime Commercial Bank which consisted of 69 branches across 24 cities.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] ABN AMRO Bank (Pakistan) Limited (Which later got merged into Royal Bank of Scotland Pakistan) was formed as the result of the US$227 million acquisition.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 21 February 2007, The Children's Investment Fund Management (TCI) hedge fund called to ask the Chairman of the Supervisory Board to actively investigate a merger, acquisition, or breakup of ABN AMRO, stating that the current stock price did not reflect the true value of the underlying assets.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] TCI asked the chairman to put its request on the agenda of the annual shareholders' meeting to be held in April 2007.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Events accelerated on 20 March 2007, when the British bank Barclays and ABN AMRO both confirmed they were in exclusive talks about a possible merger.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 28 March 2007, ABN AMRO published the agenda for the shareholders' meeting of 2007.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] It included all items requested by TCI, but with the recommendation not to follow the request for a breakup of the company.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] According to the proposed deal, RBS would receive ABN's United States operations, LaSalle, and ABN's wholesale operations; Banco Santander would take the Brazilian operations; and Fortis, the Dutch operations.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The three banks set up a joint venture, RFS Holdings (with a name based on their respective initials), to execute the transaction.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 23 April, ABN AMRO and Barclays announced the proposed acquisition of ABN AMRO by Barclays.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The deal was valued at €67 billion and included the sale of LaSalle Bank to Bank of America for €21 billion.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Two days later, the RBS-led consortium brought out its indicative offer, worth €72 billion, if ABN AMRO would abandon its sale of LaSalle Bank to Bank of America.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] During the shareholders' meeting the next day, approximately 68 percent of the shareholders voted in favor of the breakup as requested by TCI.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The sale of LaSalle was seen as obstructive by many: as a way of blocking the RBS bid, which hinged on further access to the US markets, in order to expand on the success of the group's existing American brands, Citizens Bank and Charter One.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 3 May 2007, the Dutch Investors' Association (Vereniging van Effectenbezitters), with the support of shareholders representing up to 20 percent of ABN's shares, took its case to the Dutch commercial court in Amsterdam, seeking an injunction against the LaSalle sale.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The court ruled that the sale of LaSalle could not be viewed apart from the current merger talks of Barclays with ABN AMRO and that the ABN AMRO shareholders should be able to approve other possible merger/acquisition candidates in a general shareholder meeting.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] However, in July 2007, the Dutch Supreme Court ruled that Bank of America's acquisition of LaSalle Bank could proceed and Bank of America absorbed LaSalle effective 1 October 2007.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 23 July 2007, Barclays raised its offer for ABN AMRO to €67.5bn, after securing investments from the governments of China and Singapore, but it was still short of the RBS consortium's offer.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Barclay's revised bid was worth €35.73 a share — 4.3% more than its previous offer.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The offer, which included 37% cash, remained below the €38.40-a-share offer made the week before by the RFS consortium.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The revised offer did not include an offer for La Salle Bank since ABN AMRO could proceed with the sale of that subsidiary to Bank of America.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] RBS would now settle for ABN's investment-banking division and its Asian Network.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 30 July 2007, ABN AMRO withdrew its support for Barclays' offer which was lower than the offer from the group led by RBS.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] While the Barclays offer matched ABN AMRO's "strategic vision," the board couldn't recommend it from "a financial point of view." The US$98.3bn bid from RBS, Fortis, and Banco Santander was 9.8% higher than Barclays' offer.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Barclays Bank withdrew its bid for ABN AMRO on 5 October, clearing the way for the RBS-led consortium's bid to go through, along with its planned dismemberment of ABN AMRO.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] RFS formally acquired ABN AMRO on 17 October 2007.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Fortis would receive ABN AMRO's Dutch and Belgian operations, Banco Santander would get Banco Real in Brazil, and Banca Antonveneta in Italy and RBS would get ABN AMRO's wholesale division and all other operations, including those in Asia.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Both RBS and Fortis were increasingly visibly overextended following the ABN AMRO acquisition.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 22 April 2008, RBS announced the largest rights issue in British corporate history, which aimed to raise £12billion in new capital to offset a writedown of £5.9billion resulting from the bad investments and to shore up its reserves following the purchase of ABN AMRO.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 11 July 2008, Fortis CEO Jean Votron stepped down after the ABN AMRO deal had depleted Fortis's capital.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The total worth of Fortis, as reflected by its stock value, was at that time one-third of what it had been before the acquisition, and just under the value it had paid for the Benelux activities of ABN AMRO.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 3 October 2008, Fortis was nationalised.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The Dutch government bought a number of Fortis divisions plus Fortis's share in ABN AMRO for EUR 16.8 billion.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] It subsequently announced that the parts of ABN AMRO it had acquired would be integrated with Fortis Bank Nederland (FBN) to create a new ABN AMRO.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 13 October 2008, British Prime Minister Gordon Brown announced a UK government bailout of the financial system.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The Treasury would infuse £37 billion ($64 billion, €47 billion) of new capital into Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc, Lloyds TSB and HBOS Plc, to avert financial sector collapse.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] This resulted in a total government ownership in RBS of 58%.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] As a consequence of this rescue, the chief executive of the group Fred Goodwin offered his resignation, which was duly accepted.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Later in October, Fortis announced that it would sell its stake in RFS Holdings, which included all activities that had not been transferred yet to Fortis (i.e. everything except asset management).
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In September 2009, RBS rebranded the Morgans sharedealing business in Australia as RBS Morgans.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] This followed the rebranding of the ABN AMRO Australia unit to RBS Australia in March that year.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 10 February 2010, RBS announced that branches it owned in India and the United Arab Emirates were to be rebranded under its name.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] HSBC Holdings said it would buy the Indian retail and commercial banking businesses of Royal Bank of Scotland for $1.8bn, however the deal fell-through in December 2012.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The operations owned by Santander, notably those in Italy and Brazil, were merged with Santander, sold or eliminated.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The Dutch government had obtained full control of all Fortis operations in the Netherlands, including those parts of ABN-AMRO then belonging to Fortis, at a price of €16.8bn.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The government and the De Nederlandsche Bank president have announced the merger of Dutch Fortis and ABN AMRO parts will proceed while the bank is in state ownership.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] This was completed in July 2010, when Fortis operations in the Netherlands were rebranded ABN AMRO.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In November 2008, a Belgian court dismissed a suit by shareholders of Fortis objecting to the Belgian government's handling of the Fortis/ABN AMRO transaction and subsequent break-up.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The Dutch government appointed former Dutch finance minister Gerrit Zalm as CEO to restructure and stabilise the bank, and in February 2010 the assets it owned were legally demerged from those owned by RBS.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] This demerger created two separate organisations, ABN AMRO Bank N.V. and The Royal Bank of Scotland N.V.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The former was merged with ABN AMRO Private Banking, Fortis Bank Nederland, the private bank MeesPierson (formerly owned by the original ABN AMRO and Fortis) and the diamond bank International Diamond & Jewelry Group to create ABN AMRO Group N.V., with the Fortis name being dropped on 1 July 2010.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The remaining parts of the original ABN AMRO still owned by The Royal Bank of Scotland N.V., meanwhile, were renamed, sold or closed.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] As part of the agreement with the European Commission on state aid in the restructuring, ABN AMRO sold Hollandsche Bank-Unie to Deutsche Bank in April 2010, together with another subsidiary, IFN Finance.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] ABN AMRO acquired the specialist on-line mortgage provider *Direktbank Hypotheken* as part of the nationalisation and from 1 January 2011, it stopped selling these products under this brand to the public.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] It absorbed the mortgage business into its own products under the ABN AMRO brand as well as Florius brand.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In November 2020, ABN AMRO announced it would cut 2800 jobs and sell its head offices as a plan to reduce costs, hoping to save €700 million by 2024.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In December 2023, ABN AMRO acquired BUX to boost its digital presence for an undisclosed amount.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In May 2024, ABN AMRO agreed to buy Hauck Aufhäuser Lampe (HAL), a German private bank specialised in wealth management, for 672 million euros ($730 million) from Chinese conglomerate Fosun International.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In October 2024, the Dutch government announced its plan to reduce its stake in ABN AMRO from 40.5% to 30% in the coming months.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] On 12 November 2025, ABN AMRO announced the acquisition of Dutch lender NIBC Bank for 960 million euros from American private equity firm Blackstone.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] ABN AMRO Bank has offices in 15 countries with 32,000 employees, most of whom are based in the Netherlands with only 5,000 in other countries.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] Its operations include a private banking division which focuses on high-net-worth clients in 14 countries as well as commercial and merchant banking operations that play a major role in energy, commodities and transportation markets as well as brokerage, clearing, and custody.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In April 2022, ABN AMRO Bank announced the company had signed a multi-year subscription extension with Switzerland based Banking and financial software development organisation Temenos.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The deal was made to support ABN AMRO with customer growth and overall business expansion on the Temenos Banking cloud.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The bank refers to itself as ABN AMRO in all capitals, based on an acronym of the two originating banks names Algemene Bank Nederland and the Amsterdam and Rotterdam Bank, in the second case the first two letters of each city make up the word AMRO.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The letters in 'ABN' are pronounced separately and 'AMRO' is pronounced as a word.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] For this reason some media spell the name as 'ABN Amro'.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In written text both versions are used, although the bank itself uses only the uppercase version.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] In conversations, the bank is sometimes referred to as simply ABN or AMRO bank depending on one's location around the world.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The green and yellow shield logo was designed by Landor Associates for ABN AMRO in 1991, and has been used as a brand for the bank and all its subsidiaries.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] ABN AMRO was the main sponsor of Dutch football club AFC Ajax of Amsterdam from 1991 to 2008.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The sponsor logo was at the time the only one in the world to be printed vertically down the right hand side of the front of the shirt.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] As of 2014, ABN AMRO is one of the strategic industry partners with Duisenberg School of Finance.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The bank's former art collection has been managed since the end of 2007 by a dedicated foundation, the Stichting ABN AMRO Kunstverzameling.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] As a result of the alleged fraud by Bernard Madoff, Fortis Bank Netherlands (Holding) NV lost 1 billion euros on loans from the bank (through its subsidiary Prime Fund Solutions, part of Fortis Merchant Banking) to hedge fund and as collateral investments in Bernard Madoff Investment Securities.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The Dutch government said on behalf of Fortis that a claim against the Securities and Exchange Commission would be considered.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] ABN AMRO was mentioned by the United States Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) in court filings when it sued Goldman Sachs and one of Goldman's collateralized debt obligation (CDO) traders on 16 April 2010.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] The SEC alleges that Goldman defrauded both IKB Deutsche Industriebank and ABN AMRO by its failure to disclose that the CDOs it sold to both banks were not assembled by a third party, but instead through the guidance of a hedge fund that was counterparty in the CDS transaction.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] This hedge fund, Paulson & Co., stood to reap great financial benefit in the event of default.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] ABN AMRO bank is one of the main banks financing the diamond business.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] ABN AMRO had branches in Botswana, New York, Hong Kong, Mumbai and Dubai, all of which they have sold or are in process of closing.
[src:bank-of-scotland/abn-amro] They currently only have a branch in Antwerp, where they are also shrinking their business.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-group-uk] AIB (NI) in Northern Ireland, where it offers a full range of banking services, both to business and residential customers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-ni] Allied Irish Banks' UK division, with total assets of €15.1 billion (approx £10 billion), operates in two distinct markets, Northern Ireland and Great Britain (where it operates as Allied Irish Bank (GB)), with different economies and operating environments.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-ni] AIB Group (UK) p.l.c., registered in the UK and regulated by the Financial Conduct Authority and the Prudential Regulation Authority, operates as the legal entity for the division.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-ni] In common with the other Big Four banks of Northern Ireland, First Trust Bank retained the right to issue its own banknotes, though production ceased on 30 June 2020.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-ni] These are pound sterling notes backed by their value in Bank of England notes, and should not be confused with banknotes of the former Irish pound.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-ni] Earlier note issues by the bank were made under the bank's previous names: the Provincial Bank of Ireland Ltd.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-ni] First Trust Bank's final issue of notes depicted two generic people, one male, one female.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-ni] They appear as children on the £1 and £5 notes, as middle-aged on the £10 and £20, and finally as elderly on the £50 and £100.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-ni] A £5 note featuring Dunluce Castle on the obverse and a £1 note also featuring the Girona were issued by the Provincial Bank of Ireland and by AIB, but have not been issued by First Trust Bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-ni] In February 2019, First Trust Bank ceased issuing its own banknotes in circulation and replaced them with Bank of England banknotes as they are withdrawn from circulation.
[src:bank-of-scotland/aib-ni] First Trust Bank notes could continue to be used until 30 June 2022, after which time they ceased to be legal currency but can still be paid into bank accounts, or exchanged for Bank of England notes at branches of AIB (NI).
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The **Bank of Scotland plc** (Scottish Gaelic: *Banca na h-Alba*) is a commercial and clearing bank based in Edinburgh, Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Part of the Lloyds Banking Group, the bank had a total asset amount of over £339 million in 2025.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The bank, established by the Parliament of Scotland in 1695, aimed to develop Scotland's trade with other countries and to create a stable banking system in the country.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The first bank to be established in Scotland, it is the oldest operational bank in the country, the ninth oldest bank in continuous operation globally, as well as the longest continuous issuer of banknotes in the world.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] With a history dating to the end of the 17th century, the Bank of Scotland was the first bank to have been established in Scotland, and, it is the fifth-oldest extant bank in the United Kingdom (the Bank of England having been established one year earlier).
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] It is the only commercial institution created by the Parliament of Scotland, when Scotland was an independent, sovereign state, to remain in existence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] It was the first bank in Europe to successfully print its own banknotes, and it continues to print its own sterling banknotes under legal arrangements that allow Scottish banks to issue currency.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In June 2006, the HBOS Group Reorganisation Act 2006 was passed by the Parliament of the United Kingdom, allowing the bank's structure to be simplified.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] As a result, The Governor and Company of the Bank of Scotland became Bank of Scotland plc on 17 September 2007.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Bank of Scotland has been a subsidiary of Lloyds Banking Group since 19 January 2009, when HBOS was acquired by Lloyds TSB.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] During the 1690s, public finances and economic prospects of the country were largely uncertain, with credit proving difficult to gain and cash being in relative short supply.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Although established soon after the Bank of England (1694), the Bank of Scotland was a very different institution.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Whereas the Bank of England was established specifically to finance defence spending by the English government, the Bank of Scotland was established by the Scottish government to support Scottish business, and was prohibited from lending to the government without parliamentary approval.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] John Holland was one of the bank's founders, and its first chief accountant was George Watson.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Following the establishment of the Bank of Scotland, and the raising of capital funds, the bank was able to provide loans in order to stabilise Scottish businesses and the Scottish economy.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] During its early days of operation, the Bank of Scotland acted as a means of public financial support during tough economic situations.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The condition of harvest conditions leading to poor harvests and crops led to food shortages in Scotland during the 1700s, with the Bank of Scotland providing interest-free loans to help purchase meal and grain as a result of the lack of food due to harvest conditions.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The bank was the first bank in Europe to produce banknotes.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Until the development of banknotes, coinage was the only means of cash, but it was largely scarce and unreliable.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The bank developed the idea of paper money, each with a set number of values.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Banknotes were initially issued for £5, £10, £20, £50 and £100, all of which were issued from March 1696, with a £1 note being introduced into circulation later.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The Bank of Scotland still produces its own banknotes, making the bank the longest continuous banknote issuer in the world.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The Bank of Scotland was suspected of Jacobite sympathies.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Its first rival, the Royal Bank of Scotland, was formed by royal charter in 1727.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] This led to a period of great competition between the two banks as they tried to drive each other out of business.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Although the "Bank Wars" ended in around 1751, competition soon arose from other sources, as other Scottish banks were founded throughout the country.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In response, the Bank of Scotland itself began to open branches throughout Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Following the Acts of Union in 1707, the bank supervised the reminting of the old Scottish coinage into Sterling.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] It was one of the first banks in Europe to print its own banknotes, and it continues to print its own sterling banknotes under legal arrangements that allow Scottish banks to issue currency.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Henry Dundas was Governor of the Bank of Scotland from 1790 to 1811.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] As well as governor, he was also Home Secretary in William Pitt the Younger's government.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 1792, Dundas was successful in passing the Slave Trade Bill in the House of Commons.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The bank was housed in the southern (1588) section of the Gourlay house on Melbourne Place before being moved to the customised bank building on the Mound in 1805.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The Western Bank collapsed in 1857, and the Bank of Scotland stepped in with the other Scottish banks to ensure that all the Western Bank's notes were paid.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The first branch in London opened in 1865.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In the 1950s, the Bank of Scotland was involved in several mergers and acquisitions with different banks.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 1955, the Bank merged with the Union Bank of Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The Bank also expanded into consumer credit with the purchase of Chester-based, North West Securities (Later Capital Bank).
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 1971, the Bank agreed to merge with the British Linen Bank, owned by Barclays Bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The merger saw Barclays Bank acquire a 35% stake in the Bank of Scotland, a stake it retained until the 1990s.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 1959, the Bank of Scotland became the first bank in the UK to install a computer to process accounts centrally.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] At 11:00 on 25 January 1985, the Bank of Scotland introduced HOBS (Home and Office Banking Services), an early example of remote access technology being made available to banking customers.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] This followed a small-scale service operated jointly with the Nottingham Building Society for two years but developed by the Bank of Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The new HOBS service enabled customers to access their accounts directly on a television screen, using the Prestel telephone network.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The arrival of North Sea oil to Scotland in the 1970s allowed the Bank of Scotland to expand into the energy sector.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The bank later used this expertise in energy finance to expand internationally.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The first international office opened in Houston, Texas, followed by more in the United States, Moscow and Singapore.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 1987, the bank acquired Countrywide Bank of New Zealand (later sold to Lloyds TSB in 1998).
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 1995 the bank expanded into the Australian market by acquiring Perth based Bankwest.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] A controversial period in the bank's history was the attempt in 1999 to enter the United States retail banking market via a joint venture with evangelist Pat Robertson.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The move was met with criticism from civil rights groups in the UK, owing to Robertson's controversial views on homosexuality.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The bank was forced to cancel the deal when Robertson described Scotland as a "dark land overrun by homosexuals".
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In the late 1990s, the UK financial sector market underwent a period of consolidation on a large scale.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Many of the large building societies were demutualising and becoming banks in their own right or merging with existing banks.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] For instance Lloyds Bank and TSB Bank merged in 1995 to create Lloyds TSB.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 1999, the Bank of Scotland made a takeover bid for National Westminster Bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Since the Bank of Scotland was significantly smaller than the English-based NatWest, the move was seen as an audacious and risky move.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] However, The Royal Bank of Scotland tabled a rival offer, and a bitter takeover battle ensued, with the Royal Bank the victor.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 2000, the Bank of Scotland became the first bank in the United Kingdom to introduce the concept of mobile banking, using WAP mobile phones.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] A simple and basic concept, the system allowed customers to only access account information, but it has been credited since for paving the way for the advancement and increased usage of mobile banking.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The Bank of Scotland was now the centre of other merger opportunities.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] A proposal to merge with the Abbey National was explored, but later rejected.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 2001, the Bank of Scotland and the Halifax agreed a merger to form HBOS ("Halifax Bank of Scotland").
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 2006, HBOS secured the passing of the HBOS Group Reorganisation Act 2006, a local act of Parliament that would allow the group to operate within a simplified structure.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The act allowed HBOS to make the Governor and Company of the Bank of Scotland a public limited company, Bank of Scotland plc, which became the principal banking subsidiary of HBOS.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Halifax plc and Capital Bank plc transferred their undertakings to Bank of Scotland plc, and although the Halifax brand name was retained, Halifax then began to operate under the latter company's UK banking licence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The provisions in the act were implemented on 17 September 2007.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 2008, HBOS Group agreed to be taken over by Lloyds TSB Group during the Great Recession.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In the event of Scottish independence, the constitutional role the Bank of Scotland would play remains largely unclear, and whether the bank would become the central bank of Scotland following independence.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] One proposal in the event of Scottish independence would be for Scotland to establish a new currency, the Scottish pound, which would be printed by the Central Bank of Scotland.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] During campaigning ahead of the 2014 Scottish independence referendum, the Scottish Government campaigned for Scotland to retain the Pound sterling as its currency and establish a currency union with the United Kingdom.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The Bank of Scotland would retain its status as a commercial and clearing bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The Bank of Scotland sponsored the Scottish Premier League from its inception in 1998, until the end of the 2006–2007 Scottish Premier League season, following its decision to not renew the deal in favour of investing in grassroots sport instead.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Additionally, the bank sponsored Scottish Athletics for a number of years.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Since November 2010, the Bank of Scotland Foundation has invested over £32 million to around 2,500 charities in Scotland, reaching roughly 1.2 million people by providing financial support to local services and personal support services.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Although the Bank of Scotland today is not a central bank, it retains the right (along with two other Scottish commercial banks) to issue pound sterling banknotes to this day.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] These notes are equal in value to notes issued by the Bank of England, the central bank of the United Kingdom.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Up until the middle of the 19th century, privately owned banks in Great Britain and Ireland were permitted to issue their own banknotes, and money issued by provincial Scottish, English, Welsh and Irish banking companies circulated freely as a means of payment.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The Bank of Scotland still produces its own banknotes, and is the longest continuous issuer of banknotes in the world.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 2022, the Bank of Scotland revealed the design of its £100 polymer note.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The design was the first to commemorate the contribution of an influential person from Scotland, the suffragette and medical pioneer, Dr Flora Murray.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In 1826, there was outrage in Scotland at the attempt of the United Kingdom Parliament to prevent the production of banknotes of less than five pounds face value.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Sir Walter Scott wrote a series of letters to the *Edinburgh Weekly Journal* under the pseudonym "*Malachi Malagrowther*", which provoked such a response that the government was forced to relent and allow the Scottish banks to continue printing £1 notes.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Bank of Scotland's previous note issue was in 1995, known as the *Tercentenary Series* as they were issued in the year of the three hundredth anniversary of the foundation of the bank.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] These notes are no longer in circulation.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Bank of Scotland began issuing a new series of banknotes in the Autumn of 2007, which feature the common theme of Scottish bridges.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] It will take at least three years for the current issue of Bank of Scotland notes to be phased out of circulation.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] In keeping with the bank's tradition, the front of the notes depict an image of Sir Walter Scott; the image on the 2007 series is based on the portrait of Scott painted by Henry Raeburn.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Some new security features have also been added to the new design.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] These include a metallic security thread embedded in every banknote, which contains the numerical value of the note and the note's bridge image.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] A new hologram and foil patch has been introduced on the front of the £20, £50 and £100 notes, which features the Bank of Scotland logo and the numerical value of the note.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] On 1 March 2018 the Bank of Scotland decided to withdraw all of its paper £5 and £10 notes, and fully replace them with its polymer equivalents (see below).
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] Bank of Scotland began issuing new banknotes on polymer in 2016, beginning with the £5 note.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The main theme of the bridges of Scotland are kept for this series, but have been redesigned to incorporate additional design features.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The portrait of Sir Walter Scott by Henry Raeburn is the same as the 2007 issues, but have been shifted from the centre to the right side of the notes.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The bank's headquarters, "The Mound" is featured at the centre of the note.
[src:bank-of-scotland/bank-of-scotland] The size of the notes for this series is also reduced.
